auto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Presence regarded as PR necessity\par \par \uc2 Boards expected to meet at show site\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Kevin Wale, head of GM in China, calls the World Expo which opens tonight in Shanghai the "Olympics of technology". He might as well call the $55bn (\u8364\'20\'AC41.5bn, \u163\'00\'A336bn) event the Olympics of branding: a chance for foreign multinationals to peddle their products - from Coke that freezes instantly when opened to GM cars that park themselves - to 70-100m mostly Chinese people who will attend the six-month show.\par \par \uc2 In spite of complaints of a tougher \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  in China from some foreign companies, scores of multinationals have invested heavily in the event.\par \par \uc2 Brenda Foster, head of the American Chamber of Commerce in Shanghai, says the participation of US companies - several have their own pavilions and corporate America contributed more than $60m to build the USA pavilion - "is one of many indicators that US companies are increasingly committed to the China market".\par \par \uc2 That is one reason why, when US legal restrictions prevented Washington from funding its pavilion from state coffers, Hillary Clinton, secretary of state, was able to pressure corporate America to pay for it. No one wanted America to be unrepresented at Expo - least of all companies that still, in spite of all the hardships, think China is one of the best places on earth to do business.\par \par \uc2 Numerous chief executives of Fortune 100 companies are expected to visit Expo and some foreign companies say they may bring their global board meetings to Shanghai during the event with some meetings to be held at the site itself.\par \par \uc2 Ms Foster points out that investing in a chunk of Expo turf is a good way to "advance your government relations strategy". Other foreign businessmen put it more bluntly: many multinationals felt they did not dare snub Shanghai and its Expo, the culmination of years of work and spending.\par \par \uc2 The corporate investment appears to have paid off: many of the corporate pavilions stand out as some of the most lavish, the most technologically advanced and most interesting of the 200-odd pavilions. Many of the national pavilions are lacklustre and unimaginative by comparison.\par \par \uc2 Expo has even inspired its own line of luxury goods: Chanel has launched an Expo handbag that looks like a Chinese food box and Prada has a tote with grass sprouting in front of the Oriental Pearl Tower, symbol of modern Shanghai (capitalising on Expo's theme of better integrating urban life with the natural \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ).\par \par \uc2 Coca-Cola\uc2 , which has participated in every Expo since 1933 and several before then, says world's fairs, as they used to be known, are good for business in the short term. Ted Ryan, manager of Coke's archives in Atlanta, says: "Our goal is to be considered the premier [drinks] brand: who else would be there? It has got to be \uc2 Coca-Cola\uc2 , it's just natural, like it was [for Coke] to be at the [Beijing] Olympics."\par \par \uc2 But beyond selling drinks to 70m people pounding the shade-deprived pavements of Expo, Coke says it wants to "be part of this significant moment for China". \uc2 Nestl\u233\'00\'E9\uc2 , a sponsor of the Swiss pavilion, says it wants to "be present at a major popular event that is a yardstick for China, just as the Olympics were". GKN, a sponsor of the architecturally acclaimed UK pavilion, says "we made a lot of money in China so we should do something to help out", putting Expo in the same tradition of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  as helping after the 2008 Sichuan earthquake. But another business leader puts it more cynically: for foreign business, it is plain "prudent" not to stay away.\par \par \uc2 Rising together, Page 9 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.ft.com/china"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.ft.com/china}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 ftnewspaper_20100430.xml|20100430U106.335\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c31 : \uc2 Marketing | c315 : \uc2 Conferences/Exhibitions | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpin : \uc2 FC&E Industry News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvert