stribute by email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "What is your purpose in life?" This was not a question I had expected to be asked at the start of an executive class at a top international business school. Yet it was one of the first questions put to the students enrolled in the Programme for Management Development at Iese Business School at the University of Navarra, Spain.\par \par \uc2 Steven Poelmans, associate professor of managing people and organisations at Iese, continued: "Who would you invite to your retirement party? Who would you consider to be the best person to deliver a speech about you? What would you like them to tell the others about you?"\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Such teasers appear straightforward, but they force us to confront our ideas of how we would like our life to be and what we would like to accomplish in the future. They challenge us to evaluate our social network, while reminding us that there is limited time to follow our dreams.\par \par \uc2 I began to understand my purpose in life while interviewing entrepreneurs from the Schwab Foundation for Social Entrepreneurship, a non-governmental organisation that identifies such individuals worldwide. I realised there were some amazing people who had found their purpose in life and who worked hard to change the world for the better in a professional, efficient and sometimes even profitable way. I discovered that what I wanted with my life was to do good - and to do it well.\par \par \uc2 With this in mind, I started work with Dialogue Social Enterprise (DSE), the German social franchise group behind Dialogue in the Dark - a unique exhibition where blind guides lead sighted visitors through different settings in total darkness, such as through a marketplace or on to a boat.\par \par \uc2 The experience, which has had 6m visitors since it opened more than 20 years ago, serves as a platform to experience "otherness", while encouraging co-operation and tolerance and raising awareness of the issues surrounding blindness. DSE also offers business workshops at events such as the World Economic Forum and the Hindustan Times Leadership Summit, as well as for companies.\par \par \uc2 In charge of business development and sales at DSE, I learnt that working for an NGO was economy at its core: dealing with limited resources on an everyday basis. That is what makes it challenging, but also tiring. You need to believe strongly in what you are doing to compensate for the salary gap between the non-profit and for-profit sectors.\par \par \uc2 After working on the development of social companies for several years (and studying for rewarding social entrepreneurship and executive programmes at both Insead and Stanford University), I felt the time was right to begin focusing on my own professional and personal growth.\par \par \uc2 Through Johanna Mair, associate professor of strategic development at Iese and an expert in the social sector, I learned of the Programme for Management Development, which seemed to be just what I had been looking for.\par \par \uc2 The programme consists of four modules - two of which take place in Madrid, one in Barcelona and one in New York. I am glad to revisit Madrid and New York for the remaining modules to recall the good times I had there during my studies of economics and acting. Each module lasts a week, and there are several weeks between modules.\par \par \uc2 Ahmad Rahnema, the programme director, is without doubt the best finance professor I have ever studied under. His description of sustainable growth as "positive because it creates value" has underlined my own motivation for doing the course. My aim has always been to grow in order to create more value in what I am doing and how I am doing it. I see the programme as a way to gain the tools I need to help me achieve my goals.\par \par \uc2 Our second module was entitled "Managing Value Creation". What "value" actually means in our society is open to interpretation, but the fact that the most common indicator for valuing success is through financial reward tempts us to conclude that social jobs are perceived as less "valuable". One reason for this might be because social impact is difficult to evaluate, which is why the social sector is working hard on its own measuring tools. Yet I believe companies are becoming sensitive to the social values of their customers and responding through \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities or voluntary projects.\par \par \uc2 The personal and professional exchange with my classmates - experienced managers from diverse industries - has been inspiring. The Belbin tests, which assess individuals' behaviour in a team \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , have created interesting working groups with complementing personalities.\par \par \uc2 I have learned that my preferred work style correlates with the phrase "I treat anything new as a challenge", and that "meeting people" and "getting things done" are two of my strengths, along with "being ready to lead from the front when it comes to hard work". With this in mind, I think there is room for neither hopes nor fears, but only for pure optimism.\par \par \uc2 Anke Burfeind-Herrmann is head of business development at Dialogue in the Dark/Dialogue Social Enterprise\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20100507_15315_278.xml\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 unnav : \uc2 Universidad de Navarra\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i983 : \uc2 Educational Services | ibcs : \uc2 Business/Consumer Services\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 