ell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (Copyright (c) 2010, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 LONDON -- The day \uc2 Lehman Brothers Holding Inc\uc2 . collapsed came as a blessing in disguise for 33-year-old Pierre-Loup Lesage.\par \par \uc2 The former banker had started working at the now deceased investment bank in December 2007, after finishing his M.B.A. at INSEAD, the French school outside of Paris. But he felt he had gone off-course.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "Everyone was doing it: as you start your M.B.A. you apply to work in a bank, you do your summer internship there and then by the end of your degree you start a 60K job plus bonus," he explains. "Although the crisis hadn't really hit there were some signs of it, and being in finance was not what I wanted to do anyway. I was impressed by what other people were doing and lost my way."\par \par \uc2 So when he was laid off following the collapse of \uc2 Lehman Brothers\uc2  in September 2008, Mr. Lesage, originally from France, saw a chance to redirect his career.\par \par \uc2 "I really wanted to work in development but hadn't even tried to apply to places I would have loved to work for, like the United Nations or the Global Fund," he explains. He finally ended up working in Madagascar for the Clinton Foundation.\par \par \uc2 Like Mr. Lesage, there are an increasing number of recent graduates who have started to look at more socially related roles to put in practice the knowledge and skills of their expensive M.B.A.s at elite European universities.\par \par \uc2 Top universities in Europe said admissions rose as a result of the financial crisis, as individuals sought refuge in academia throughout the downturn. And out of those who studied throughout the crisis, there has also been a fall in the number of people pursuing careers in finance and opting for more socially related fields.\par \par \uc2 Also a factor: the rise in nongovernmental organizations and others in the field, which often benefit from the same types of management techniques that you learn though an M.B.A. program.\par \par \uc2 France's HEC School of Management, for one, has seen a jump from only 1% of recent graduates going into NGO-related jobs before the crisis in 2008, to 8% last year.\par \par \uc2 The shift away from the traditional banking and industry jobs, albeit small, is thought to be long-lasting, according to those who monitor this market closely.\par \par \uc2 "The real and genuine increase in interest of careers for non-for-profit organizations and public service among our students is new but is not something that will be short-lived," says Valerie Gauthier, associate dean at the HEC M.B.A. Program. "It doesn't mean that they won't have successful careers and make a good living, but return on investment and making money is no longer the only objective," she explains.\par \par \uc2 Ms. Gauthier believes universities are also playing a role in this renewed interest for alternative career paths.\par \par \uc2 "As part of our curriculum we bring a more global understanding of what are the challenges and real issues for tomorrow's businesses'," she says. "We bring speakers, like philosophers, that address those kinds of issues. When we recruit people we systematically ask them: what have you done in your life to serve your community?"\par \par \uc2 Nuria Guilera, M.B.A. marketing director at ESADE, agrees that this shift will be more permanent. "New generations of graduates are increasingly discussing business ethics and the responsibility,"the Barcelona-based executive says. "There are booms and fads, of course, but here in our university we are making sure \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  is an integral part of our curriculum."\par \par \uc2 Although Cass Business School in London doesn't keep figures that point to this new trend, Sarah Dunbar -- relationship manager at the university -- says she's noticed a change in what students are looking to gain from an M.B.A.\par \par \uc2 "We have noticed how applications coming through are from students typically looking to do something to benefit society," she explains. Recent applications have highlighted "a lack of sense of reward and purpose" from aspiring students "looking to make a difference," Ms. Dunbar says.\par \par \uc2 Why the sudden interest in using an M.B.A. for different purposes than financial gains? "It may be a reflection of the current times," Ms. Dunbar says. "While the bulk of students are still pursuing M.B.A.s to increase their earnings, a proportion do feel there are opportunities outside banking."\par \par \uc2 Jan Rihak, a Swiss national currently studying his M.B.A. at the University of Cambridge in England, says elements of finance are still relevant in today's business \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and he believes not-for-profit organizations should be run as a company.\par \par \uc2 He adds: "I am convinced ethical considerations will be more prominent now" following the crisis in the financial system. "The notion of maximizing shareholder value is relevant to a certain extent, but it has to be balanced to take a wider picture," he says.\par \par \uc2 "I am not interest in shuffling money around and not having that much of a real impact and the possibility to add value to society," says Mr. Rihak, who during his M.B.A. has already set up the U.K. branch of Aiducation International, a not-for-profit organization dedicated to giving people access to education.\par \par \uc2 French philosopher Theodore Zeldin, who talks to students at HEC, says he's seen an increase in M.B.A. students sharing similar values to those of Mr. Rihak. "We are living in a generation that's seeking a different kind of life. M.B.A.s were invented a century ago and were made by people who saw work as a means to obtain a product," he says.\par \par \uc2 "People are now rethinking work and want to expand their horizons. How will retailing develop people spiritually? It's not constructed for that. Work has become mechanic. Your career means a horse race. But [some] people increasingly regard stress as not being part of a successful life," he says.\par \par \uc2 "You have to ask yourself: do you want to taste the food or do you want to eat your hamburger as fast as you can," Mr. Zeldin says.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.djreprints.com/link/DJRFactiva.html?FACTIVA=weco20100511000017"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 License this article from Dow Jones Reprint Service}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 lehbro : \uc2 Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i814 : \uc2 Banking | i831 : \uc2 Financial Investments | i83101 : \uc2 Investment Banking | ibnk : \uc2 Banking/Credit | iinv : \uc2 Investing/Securities\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\