ha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 These descriptions of the institutions on the shortlist for the 2010 Sustainable Emerging Markets Bank of the Year, Achievement in Basic Needs Financing, Banking at the Base of the Pyramid and Sustainable Investor of the Year awards are based on information provided by them ahead of tonight's awards dinner in London.\par \par \uc2 Sustainable Emerging Markets Bank of the Year\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Africa/Middle East\par \par \uc2 BMCE Bank\uc2 , Morocco\par \par \uc2 The recent adoption by Morocco's \uc2 BMCE Bank\uc2  of the Equator Principles highlights its commitment to sustainable development, a strategy implemented since the bank's privatisation, notably through the establishment in 1995 of \uc2 BMCE Bank\uc2  Foundation for Education and \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . As the first African signatory of Unep FI (United Nations \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  Programme Finance Initiative) in February 2000, \uc2 BMCE Bank\uc2  has been committed to the Unep statement by financial institutions on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and sustainable development, as well as its active membership in the Banking Commission, the African Task Force and the Water & Finance Work Stream. In 2008, BMCE established practices and procedures to assess and manage social and environmental risks for all its investment loans. The bank underwent a strategic restructuring in the field of sustainable development, recognising that the challenges it faced were better dealt with not only by giving back to the community and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but by incorporating such considerations into its methods of doing business. BMCE has thus taken a further step in separating sustainability in finance from philanthropy in society, recognising that both are complementary constituents of the bank's commitment to its shareholders, stakeholders and local citizenry.\par \par \uc2 Equity Bank, Kenya\par \par \uc2 Equity Bank (EBL) is Kenya's largest bank by number of accounts (with more than 3.4m account holders or a 45 per cent domestic market share) and among the top three by market capitalisation. It has developed a successful sustainability-focused hybrid of a microfinance institution and commercial bank that provides banking services to the previously unbanked in Kenya. This has been achieved with a tailored distribution and innovative customer service strategy that socially and economically empowers its customers. EBL has integrated environmental and social responsibility into its corporate policy and staff training programmes. Its approach of providing accessible, attractive and affordable banking services to the unbanked in Kenya, while operating commercially, ensures that its CSR-focused microfinance service offering is economically sustainable. This is demonstrated by a solid track record of high growth in customers, deposits, assets and profits, generating an impressive 20 per cent return on equity in 2008.\par \par \uc2 Nedbank, South Africa\par \par \uc2 Nedbank Group\uc2  is one of the four largest banking groups in South Africa. Listed on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange since 1969, it offers a comprehensive range of wholesale and retail banking. With a clear focus on being a bank for all, it operates primarily in South and southern Africa, where it enjoys a vast footprint, a significant share of the market, and a highly diverse client base. Its ultimate objective is to preserve our planet for current and future generations, and make life better for as many people as it can along the way. Its sustainability strategy brings together economic, environmental, social and cultural concerns to unlock synergies across the business. In 2009, Nedbank became the first South African bank to commit to carbon neutrality. As a result of the sustainability initiatives undertaken over the past five years, \uc2 Nedbank Group\uc2  finds itself more resilient and adaptable, and more focused on moving forward as an organisation that not only lives out its brand aspiration to Make Things Happen, but also influences others to do the same.\par \par \uc2 Asia\par \par \uc2 BRAC Bank, Bangladesh\par \par \uc2 BRAC Bank (BBL) started operations in 2001 with a goal to provide banking services to the underserved population of Bangladesh by intermediating funds from urban to rural areas. The majority of its financing is to the SME sector with the aim of assisting economic development. In so doing, BBL has generated employment for more than 1m people and contributed to economic welfare by enhancing the standard of living. It has also addressed forestry and child labour issues at various policy levels. BBL has initiatives in financing renewable energy and waste management, capacity building in SMEs, increasing financial literacy for the SME sector, financing women entrepreneurs and agriculture, and increasing service quality. The bank has the highest market share in SME financing and women entrepreneur financing in Bangladesh. It is one of the 11 founder-member banks of the Global Alliance for Banking on Values (GABV), which has pledged to provide sustainable banking services to 1bn people by 2020.\par \par \uc2 Industrial Bank, China\par \par \uc2 Founded in August 1988 and headquartered in Fuzhou City, Fujian Province, Industrial Bank was one of the first joint-stock commercial banks approved by the State Council and the People's Bank of China. In recent years, the bank has incorporated the concept of sustainable development into its development strategy and corporate governance. This concept has been applied to all aspects of its operations and management, in order to induce a change in thinking in relation to the pattern of development, the innovation of business models, the efficient allocation of resources, the improvement of incentive and restraint mechanisms, and the enhancement of service efficiency. The bank has gradually developed a sustainable development pattern with its own characteristics, applying social responsibility to the provision of services and expansion of its business, thus enhancing its own value and strengthening its core competitiveness.\par \par \uc2 YES Bank, India\par \par \uc2 YES Bank, a private sector Indian bank founded in May 2004, is a state-of-the-art, customer-centric and service-driven institution catering to the "future businesses of India", and is an outcome of the commitment of its founder, Rana Kapoor, managing director and chief executive. As the professionals' bank of India, YES Bank is "creating and sharing value" for all its stakeholders. Its focus on governance and good corporate citizenship, actualised through its Responsible Banking approach, forms an integral part of its strategic vision. The bank's sustainability strategy works on two levels - Sustainability in Thought and Sustainability in Action - and is focused on delivering holistic financial products and services across a broad spectrum including clean technology, renewable energy, SRI, water management, social infrastructure (health and education) and sustainable livelihoods. Using a multi-stakeholder approach in engaging with industry, its peers, academia, media, civil society and policymakers, YES Bank continuously works towards mainstreaming sustainability within the Indian context. Its retail branches, for instance, all play an important role in their communities through YES Community engagement activities.\par \par \uc2 Eastern Europe\par \par \uc2 Raiffeisenbank (Bulgaria)\par \par \uc2 Raiffeisenbank (Bulgaria) continued in 2009 to draw on the experience of RI/RZB Group in adopting EU policies, thus ensuring its own sustainable development. Being a universal bank, Raiffeisenbank continued to apply sustainability standards across its key business lines. It supported individuals' efforts to significantly cut down energy consumption and improve energy efficiency, and also funded large-scale projects under the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD)'s REECL/EERECL programmes. Access to financing and job creation for SMEs, farmers and entrepreneurs was provided under two EBRD Rural Credit Lines. As part of its \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Raiffeisenbank follows a consistent charity and sponsorship policy. In 2009 it initiated its own major charity campaign, supporting more than 30 healthcare, social, educational and cultural projects of significant importance for society. The wide public attention and involvement of 2,800 bank employees, who donated their own money, helped popularise the campaign.\par \par \uc2 RZB Group\par \par \uc2 The RZB Group pioneered the opening up and modernisation of central and eastern Europe (CEE)'s banking markets and is one of the largest banking groups in the region, with more than 3,000 branches, around 60,000 employees, and more than 15m private individual and corporate customers. The RZB Group's CEE sustainability strategy is built on a long-term commitment to the region, with a strong focus on financing renewables, and with a trustworthy internal environmental and social risk management in place. RZB Group's decentralised structure and its corporate responsibility strategy are both based on the three core challenges associated with regional sustainability in CEE - \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including climate change; society, with a focus on diversity, youth, education, human resources and corporate compliance; and economic sustainability, against the backdrop of persistently difficult und diverse market conditions in the 17 CEE markets that RZB Group serves: Albania, Belarus, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Bulgaria, Croatia, Czech Republic, Hungary, Kazakhstan, Kosovo, Moldavia, Poland, Romania, Serbia, Slovakia, Slovenia, Russia and Ukraine.\par \par \uc2 Industrial Development Bank of Turkey (TSKB)\par \par \uc2 As a privately owned development and investment bank, TSKB has been supporting the sustainable development of Turkey for 60 years and is a pioneer in renewable energy corporate lending and project financing. In the areas of environmental and renewable energy loans, TSKB has completed the largest number of projects in Turkey. Always taking into consideration the environmental and social aspects of projects financed, it is the first Turkish bank to be certified with the ISO 14001 Environmental Management System Standard. TSKB incorporates environmental awareness into its banking services and corporate culture, and conveys its mission through the slogan \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 : Our Priority. In 2009, it was admitted to the UN Environmental Programme Finance Initiative (Unep FI) and became the first Turkish carbon-neutral bank. It has also published the first sustainability report in Turkey's banking sector.\par \par \uc2 Latin America\par \par \uc2 Banco do Brasil\par \par \uc2 Social and environmental responsibility has always been present in \uc2 Banco do Brasil\uc2 's policies and strategies. Aligned with the global movement linked to climate change, \uc2 Banco do Brasil\uc2  participated in several discussion forums and made new and important national and international commitments in 2009, such as membership of Platform Business Climate and the UN Caring for Climate initiative. All these undertakings are consolidated in BB Agenda 21, which guides the actions of the bank in its sustainable management practices, products, services and investments. The several credit lines with socio-environmental characteristics in the portfolio of the bank totalled 6.69 per cent of its total portfolio last year. The Regional Sustainable Development Strategy mobilised resources of approximately US$2.8bn. There have also been many advances in environmental management, such as the publication of the Bank's first inventory of greenhouse gas emissions. To be a reference point for sustainability is part of \uc2 Banco do Brasil\uc2 's strategy.\par \par \uc2 For \uc2 Ita\u250\'00\'FA Unibanco\uc2  and \uc2 Banco Santander Brasil\uc2 , see entries in "Five on the shortlist for Bank of the Year"\par \par \uc2 Achievement in Basic Needs Financing\par \par \uc2 Acumen Fund\uc2 , US\par \par \uc2 Acumen Fund\uc2  is a non-profit global venture fund that uses entrepreneurial approaches to solve the problems of global poverty. It seeks to prove that small amounts of philanthropic capital, combined with large doses of business acumen, can build thriving enterprises that serve vast numbers of the poor. The fund believes that pioneering entrepreneurs will ultimately find the solutions to poverty. The entrepreneurs \uc2 Acumen Fund\uc2  supports are focused on offering critical services - water, health, housing, and energy - through innovative, market-oriented approaches. The key is "patient capital". The fund uses philanthropic capital to make disciplined investments - loans or equity, not grants - that yield both financial and social returns. Any financial returns we receive are recycled into new investments. Over time, we have refined the \uc2 Acumen Fund\uc2  investment model, built a world-class global team with offices in four countries, and learned what does and does not work in growing businesses that serve low-income people.\par \par \uc2 Banco de Galicia y Buenos Aires\uc2 , Argentina\par \par \uc2 Banco Galicia was founded in 1905 and is one of the largest private banks in Argentina. It is the only financial entity in Argentina that has adopted the Equator Principles and is ISO 9001 and 14001 certified. Grupo Financiero Galicia is the controlling shareholder of Banco Galicia and its shares trade under the ticker symbol GGAL on the Buenos Aires Stock Exchange and Nasdaq in the US. Galicia has gone beyond corporate services, providing a huge range of retail products focusing on the needs of middle- and low-income clients through credit lines and the issuance of credit cards. In terms of overall lending, basic needs financing accounts for more than 50 per cent of the total portfolio. The bank's activities have expanded significantly to reach unbanked segments without lowering risk standards. The development of new credit lines has been a contributing factor to Galicia becoming a second-tier bank for microfinance institutions.\par \par \uc2 Mahindra and Mahindra Financial Services, India\par \par \uc2 Mahindra and Mahindra Financial Services (Mahindra Finance) is India's leading non-banking finance company (NBFC) focused on rural and semi-urban areas and the largest rural NBFC with a reach that extends beyond 450 branches. It is the second largest asset financing company of India, with a value of assets under management exceeding $2.2bn. It is the largest financier of tractors in India and the leading financier of Mahindra vehicles. Since its inception, Mahindra Finance has established more than 1m customer relationships. The company has a unique business model based on the foundations of social inclusiveness, which serves the "bottom of pyramid" customers. Mahindra Finance has a subsidiary, Mahindra Insurance Brokers, to distribute insurance products, which has tie-ups with the various leading insurance companies. Another focus area for the company is to provide loans for rural housing requirements, both for construction and upgrading of houses, through its subsidiary Mahindra Rural Housing Finance.\par \par \uc2 One Acre Fund, Kenya\par \par \uc2 One Acre Fund empowers hungry farm families in east Africa to pull themselves out of poverty. Its innovative approach to lending and repayment helps smallholder farmers - who spend roughly 65 per cent of their income on food - to double their farm income and increase their food security. The One Acre Fund "market bundle" includes group formation, seed and fertiliser on credit, training on the use of these farm inputs, and market facilitation.\par \par \uc2 Scotiabank Peru\par \par \uc2 Scotiabank's presence in Peru dates back to 1997. But it was not until 2006, as part of an expansion in Latin America, that \uc2 Bank of Nova Scotia\uc2  acquired majority holdings in two important banking institutions - \uc2 Banco Wiese Sudameris\uc2  and \uc2 Banco Sudamericano\uc2  - and combined them to create Scotiabank Peru. It is now Peru's third largest financial group, with a staff of 9,300 and more than 2m customers. It has strengthened its consumer and microfinance presence with the acquisition of Banco de Trabajo and the launch last year of CrediScotia Financiera, a specialised channel for microbusiness and consumer finance that reaches the lowest socio-economic groups and those excluded from the banking system. \b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  is fundamental to Scotiabank Peru's business. It is an opportunity to build better relationships with its customers, employees, shareholders and community partners while fulfilling its social, economic, environmental and ethical responsibilities. The bank has initiated various programmes to address its direct and indirect impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and routinely factors environmental considerations into its strategic decision-making as well as its lending and investment.\par \par \uc2 Banking at the Base of the Pyramid\par \par \uc2 Financial Information Network and Operations, India\par \par \uc2 Financial Information Network and Operations (FINO) provides small loan products to the entrepreneurial poor in India. These are aimed at the set of individuals at the bottom of the pyramid who have no access to formal financial services, primarily due to a lack of awareness and documentary evidence required to open a bank account, as well as a lack of confidence about approaching banks. The target customers have entrepreneurial traits, and are mainly local fruit and vegetable vendors, street hawkers and subsistence dairy farmers, in both urban and rural communities. The programme reaches out to customers across the states of Maharashtra, Tamil Nadu, Uttar Pradesh, Gujarat and Delhi. The product entails tangible and intangible socio-economic and observed environmental benefits for the end-customer. FINO's biometric smart card and mobile technology-based low-cost doorstep delivery model makes it sustainable and scalable across all geographies in India.\par \par \uc2 Five Talents, UK\par \par \uc2 Five Talents (a UK registered charity) has played a key role in delivering an innovative "holistic" microfinance pilot project in the village of Lietnhom, southern Sudan, assisting post-conflict transformational development in an area still recovering from 20 years of civil war. The project is situated where no other financial services or training exists within 100 miles, combining basic literacy training with business skills development, savings mobilisation and the provision of microcredit. It has demonstrated significant financial and socio-economic impact, using a sustainable model that is ready to be expanded and replicated elsewhere in southern Sudan and beyond.\par \par \uc2 MAP International, US\par \par \uc2 MAP International partners with emerging market countries to deploy a fully integrated Electronic Identification and Financial Infrastructure Platform and leverages the latest in mobile technologies to enable financial inclusion for the un-banked and under-banked citizens of these countries. MAP's unique Public Private Partnership Model allows governments to deploy the most technologically advanced financial systems at very limited upfront costs, providing a sustainable banking infrastructure for the future benefit of the country. MAP's platform creates unique biometric bank debit-ID cards for people in even the most remote areas and after integrating them into the banking platform provides the newly banked with its Financial Switch - multiple channels of access to their accounts via a network of ATMs and specially adapted point-of-sale devices as well as from their mobile phones. MAP's agent network provides the access to cash. MAP also offers mobile carriers a fully functioning and open mobile banking platform that integrates into MAP's national Switch network.\par \par \uc2 MicroEnsure, UK\par \par \uc2 MicroEnsure is an insurance intermediary dedicated to serving the poor throughout the developing world. It serves around 3.5m people with an affordable and appropriate range of products including life, property, health and weather index based insurance. With a $24.2m grant from the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation in 2007, the pace of expansion accelerated and more ambitious growth targets became a reality. MicroEnsure's aim is to achieve sustainability for insurance companies, product distributors, and clients. Key to minimising the cost of micro-insurance is the sophisticated MIS system employed in its back office processing that tracks details of clients covered, collects premiums and administers claims. By acting as an intermediary, the organisation is well-positioned to extend insurance coverage very efficiently with simple, understandable, and scalable products. Its extensive market research and insurance expertise ensures that it can design products that address the real financial risk management needs of the poor.\par \par \uc2 Standard Chartered Bank, UAE\par \par \uc2 Standard Chartered's microfinance programme adopts a wholesale approach, providing the full range of banking products and services to microfinance institutions in Asia, Africa, and the Middle East as well as socially responsible investors in the Americas and Europe. The objective is to provide access to finance to those who are either unserved or under-served by the mainstream financial sector. Since starting in 2006, the microfinance programme has already provided banking services in 20 countries, with $540m in loan funding to 17 countries. The bank estimates that this has benefited almost 3.6m people who were excluded from the financial sector. The microfinance programme also includes investing in technical assistance initiatives, allowing the bank to build on its expertise in governance, risk management and human resources and share best practices with its microfinance partners. It has also supported research and innovation, promoted industry events and, where possible, helped to influence regulatory policy.\par \par \uc2 Sustainable Investor of the Year\par \par \uc2 Acumen Fund\uc2 , US (see above)\par \par \uc2 Calvert Foundation, US\par \par \uc2 Calvert Foundation has blazed a new trail that makes it possible for everyday people to finance non-profits and community organisations that revitalise communities, develop affordable housing, build micro- and small growing businesses, support Fair Trade farming, further environmental sustainability, and more. It uses investor capital to make loans on flexible terms to groups whose qualifications fall outside conventional underwriting guidelines. These groups then pay back their loans reliably with interest - creating a sustainable virtuous cycle. Calvert Foundation helps more than 6,000 caring investors incorporate a unique element into their investment portfolios: the desire to help poor communities. Investing with the foundation provides a guaranteed return (up to 3 per cent) and brings hope and opportunity to underprivileged families throughout the US and around the globe. Calvert Foundation manages more than $350m raised through sales of the Community Investment Note and other programmes.\par \par \uc2 FINCA International, US and \uc2 Deutsche Bank\uc2 , Germany\par \par \uc2 On November 10, 2009, the FINCA Fund became the first microfinance debt fund to raise money after the worldwide economic crises struck in 2008. At a difficult time for the capital markets, the transaction provided important subordinated debt for seven of FINCA International's affiliated MFIs (microfinance institutions) in the developing world that had been unable to grow due to capital constraints in the difficult market. The fund represents the first transaction where a microfinance network has tapped the capital markets under a single branded umbrella entity, a new way for networks to fund-raise efficiently. It is the first microfinance fund with investments from the private sector only, even in junior tranches historically filled by development agencies, demonstrating that the private sector will take all levels of risk in social endeavours. With its attractive structure and FINCA's brand, the fund was 100 per cent oversubscribed and drew socially motivated investors new to microfinance who are interested in supporting microfinance in the future.\par \par \uc2 Global \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  Fund\uc2 , US\par \par \uc2 Global \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  Fund\uc2 's portfolios demonstrated great resilience and delivered strong liquidity in 2009. The firm achieved record-setting financial performance, with $106m in new investments, and $105m of recognised capital appreciation. Total return for the year was nearly 35 per cent. GEF companies also provided greater environmental, social and economic development benefits than ever. They generated renewable energy, managed sustainable timberlands, and sold environmental equipment and services on five continents - offsetting CO2 emissions and creating local jobs in the process. The financial highlights of 2009 were the successful NYSE IPO of \uc2 Duoyuan Global Water\uc2 , a manufacturer of water treatment equipment for the Chinese market, and the agreement to sell Unirac, a leading US solar solutions company, for a 15 times return. Both transactions exemplify GEF's dedication to long-term, growth capital investments in replicable and scalable business models that capture new markets by making positive contributions to environmental and social objectives.\par \par \uc2 Ventureast Fund Advisors, India\par \par \uc2 Ventureast is an unabashed commercial investor that attempts to make significant social and environmental impact while generating financial returns in the top quartile or higher. Nowhere does Ventureast claim its social and environmental goals publicly. It does not seek grant funding, and has been funded equally by commercial investors as well as developmental financial institutions. The companies it invests in have received and continue to receive follow-on investments from purely social impact-oriented investors, confirming the social and environmental impact of Ventureast's investments. Its investing approach has been one of entering segments where there is little competition, but innovatively and in a capital efficient manner. This approach naturally leads Ventureast to underserved markets such as the rural and digital-divide segments, and to such industry segments as healthcare delivery, agriculture-related, digital connectivity, clean \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 -related, etc. Applying technology innovation (telemedicine services through low-bandwidth connectivity, organic farming expansion, etc) and financial structuring (equity-like investing for micro-entrepreneurs, etc) allows it to mitigate risk and address the longer timeframes required for these investments.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpa