ly acknowledges, some of Timberland's investors were wondering whether Mr Swartz had indeed ended up in the right office. "Our critics were plain, saying 'you are doing a crappy job'," he says, displaying his unusual readiness to admit to shortcomings in his own past performance.\par \par \uc2 The crisis had an unlikely source, as the company's yellow work boots fell out of favour with the world of hip-hop fashion (although not before inspiring the naming of the artist and music producer Timbaland).\par \par \uc2 Under the leadership of Mr Swartz, who became CEO in 1998, Timberland pursued the sales boom. It now had to confront what he calls "the reality of laziness in terms of strategy and sloppiness in terms of execution".\par \par \uc2 He talks with friendly animation and, having once studied Proust, Faulkner and Joyce as part of a comparative literature course at Brown University, he sometimes piles up his words and metaphors to get to his point - in sentences that may or may not end. He is a man who seems to wrestle with questions about his management style and the changes at the company, issues that are clearly wrapped up with his own identity.\par \par \uc2 He feels the responsibility of his family legacy: "What's it like to confront failure in a family business? . . . When you are not performing, it's like you are attacking the reputation of your father; it's like you are diminishing the story of your grandfather."\par \par \uc2 And, as an orthodox Jew who reads the Talmud daily, he feels the responsibility of his religious belief and tries to conduct his business and his life according to the principles of his faith. "I am an engaged parishioner to my faith. If I think there's a big gap between belief and execution in corporate governance, I also think there's a big gap in what I espouse and how I live. And I investigate both gaps daily," he says.\par \par \uc2 Under his leadership, Timberland has become a leader among socially and environmentally responsible businesses in the US. From his window at the company's headquarters in Stratham, New Hampshire, about 50 miles north of Boston, he can look out over a set of recently installed solar panels, and several neat seasonal vegetable gardens adjacent to the car park, which are tended by staff using company paid community service hours. The produce is sold to aid the state's main food bank. Beyond the HQ, the company has set industry standards for its environmental reporting.\par \par \uc2 So when Mr Swartz and his team embarked upon the effort to return Timberland to profitable growth three years ago, the conversations involved not just operating profits, but "how to do that in terms of a business that's associated with values and principles". And it involved, he says, asking questions.\par \par \uc2 "As always the decisions aren't hard, the questions are hard. Do you have the right questions? Because if you have the right questions, and you have the right people, that care, and we do have bright caring people, you will almost always get a right answer."\par \par \uc2 Supported by Mike Harrison, the company's British-born president and a former executive of \uc2 Procter & Gamble\uc2  who has a more conventional management style, the company undertook a strategic review. It was, he says, a process that involved sitting down as a team and "really beating the hell out of each other" before he synthesised a simple but characteristically metaphorical three-point strategy: strengthen the "heat and height" of the Timberland brand; focus geographically on "one fortress city at a time"; and develop "a nimble and sustainable" supply chain.\par \par \uc2 But during all the discussions on cost saving, Mr Swartz points out that "no one said a way to get our gross margin back up would be to relax our labour standards" or to take other steps that would undermine the ethical values that have become an important part of the outdoor brand identity. "It wasn't because people were afraid to make suggestions . . . They told me everything from change your hairstyle to shoot yourself; the range of constructive suggestions was voluminous. But not against the values issue."\par \par \uc2 The restructuring included closing retail stores in North America with related, painful layoffs at HQ; reducing costs by licensing most of its branded clothing business; and focusing its marketing efforts on its strongest markets. The company's problems, however, meant that when the 2008 financial crash came, "we were already in defensive mode, already in 'how do we cope with this downturn'. The economic thing deepened the descent, but I never thought the hull was going to crush".\par \par \uc2 Timberland's position was helped by having no debt - a legacy of an earlier setback, after Mr Swartz led an overly rapid expansion under his father that almost ended in bankruptcy. ("We had a meeting or two with the bankers where it really hung in the balance," he says).\par \par \uc2 This year, revenues have started to grow again for the first time since 2006, when they hit $1.56bn. Gross margins are expanding, and the share price is back above $18 after dipping below $10 late last year. The company has a new "mantra of modesty" of "fewer things done better".\par \par \uc2 Timberland's long-term objective has become simple, if ambitious: to be the leading outdoor brand in the world.\par \par \uc2 The brand, Mr Swartz argues, is now back on track. But he is still wrestling with questions, including the ethically charged strategic objective of developing a better supply chain, in the face of what he sees as "the dissolution of the Far East as a cheap and easy way to make shoes".\par \par \uc2 Timberland, he says, is exploring new models of regional production in India and other locations, focused on efficiencies through good infrastructure rather than relying on comparatively low wages, while its decision to retain ownership of its factory in the Dominican Republic "all of a sudden looks clever".\par \par \uc2 He is still deeply concerned about the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and about the comparative insignificance of efforts by companies such as his to reduce their impact: "If you died tomorrow, how would you view that? . . . Not good enough is how I conclude."\par \par \uc2 He is worried about the increasing bitterness and "demagoguery" of the political debate in the US. He is not convinced that a consumer recovery is properly under way.\par \par \uc2 And now, as the father of three sons, he is still asking himself big questions about whether he is adhering to the principles of his faith. "In my limited experience, it is all about the questions," he says.\par \par \uc2 The CV\par \par \uc2 Born: 196O Education: 1982 Bachelor of Arts in comparative literature from Brown University 1984 MBA from Tuck School of Business, Dartmouth College Career: 1986 Joins father Sydney at Timberland 1988 Takes leading role in groundbreaking public-private relationship with City Year, a national youth service organisation 1991 Named chief operating officer 1998 Becomes chief executive 2002 Receives Ron Brown presidential award for work on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  Interests: Married with three sons. Enjoys literature, hiking and wilderness camping. Avid fan of the Boston Red Sox\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 tmbco : \uc2 Timberland Co\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\