5 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Financial Times (FT.Com)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2010 The Financial Times Ltd. All rights reserved. Please do not cut and paste FT articles and redistribute by email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Google\uc2  this week announced plans to invest in a $5bn project to build an underwater transmission network that will transport electricity from wind farms off the Mid-Atlantic coast to homes in the US. The move left some baffled and questioning why the US online advertising and search engine operator was spending some of its $30bn cash pile on what appears to be a peripheral investment in alternative energy.\par \par \uc2 "We believe in investing in projects that make good business sense and further the development of renewable energy. We're willing to take calculated risks on early stage ideas and projects that can have dramatic impacts while offering attractive returns," \uc2 Google\uc2  said in a blog post.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 In fact investing in green energy and green technology has an increasing logic for companies like \uc2 Google\uc2 , Amazon and \uc2 Microsoft\uc2 , as they move to show their green credentials and offset the impact of the large amounts of power and water that are used running vast servers centres at secret locations around the world. As well as housing servers for their own use, many of these data centres are increasingly being used to rent out server capacity to other companies.\par \par \uc2 According to some estimates, 25 per cent of all the servers sold globally are bought by just four companies - \uc2 Google\uc2 , Amazon, \uc2 Microsoft\uc2  and \uc2 Yahoo\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Computing and communications technologies as a whole are estimated to be responsible for as much as 3 per cent of global carbon emissions. And analysts say a large proportion of those emissions are derived from inefficiently run servers either stored inside an individual company's premises or in large data centres.\par \par \uc2 The statistics have fed into a wider shift in thinking over the last few years, whereby technology companies are increasingly seeing the \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  benefits and cost advantages to adopting green technologies.\par \par \uc2 "There is a massive incentive for providers to drive the green agenda, because the fundamental truth is that if you upgrade to modern technology, it will be better for the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," says Kenny Fraser, a partner at PwC.\par \par \uc2 Google\uc2 , for example, started investing in renewable energy in 2007 aware of the impact the "extensive computer infrastructure" needed to keep its operations running was having on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The undersea project will not provide power directly for \uc2 Google\uc2  but the company says it wants to be a "good environmental steward and do things that make good business sense". Other initiatives, however, such as a recent power purchase agreement with a wind farm in Iowa are more directly linked to reducing carbon emissions at its data centres.\par \par \uc2 "Generating that electricity requires energy, and as our business grows, we want to make sure we minimize our impact on the Earth's climate." It's a commitment that founders \uc2 Larry Page\uc2  and \uc2 Sergey Brin\uc2  are known to take a personal interest in.\par \par \uc2 Others technology groups are increasingly highlighting their green credentials.\par \par \uc2 Last year \uc2 Microsoft\uc2  opened a high tech centre near Dublin, its first large scale computing centre and home to its Azure cloud computing platform. In July, \uc2 Cisco\uc2  announced a tie-up with Malaysia's Teliti Datacentres to build a green data centre on the outskirts of Kuala Lumpur. This month \uc2 Yahoo\uc2  announced plans to turn an old manufacturing plant in Switzerland into a new "environmentally friendly" data centre.\par \par \uc2 And just this week \uc2 Capgemini\uc2 , the European IT services group, officially launched Merlin, a state-of-the-art data centre built on a brownfield site on the outskirts of Swindon in the UK.\par \par \uc2 Richard Dicketts, chief executive of global infrastructure management at \uc2 Capgemini\uc2 , says Merlin is part of the group's long-term drive to improve efficiency and will allow it to meet "contractual imperatives to deliver environmental efficiency".\par \par \uc2 Capgemini\uc2 's centre is essentially a large warehouse in which recyclable, stackable containers hold batches of servers that are more efficiently cooled and run. The design uses 30 per cent less water than traditional centres, 100 per cent fresh air cooling and boasts a power usage effectiveness (PUE) rating of 1.08, compared to an industry average of 2 to 2.5.\par \par \uc2 Mr Dicketts points out that the push towards greener data centres and cloud computing also has obvious cost benefits for customers.\par \par \uc2 Cloud computing - the buzz phrase used to describe the provision of computer power to customers over the internet from remote hosted data centres - enables companies to reduce carbon emissions by shifting their IT functions. It also has sizeable cost advantages.\par \par \uc2 Frank Modruson, chief information officer at \uc2 Accenture\uc2 , says that "cost and green technology are completely aligned". The consulting firm, which now has 80 per cent of its own IT virtualized, says the shift towards "cloud is largely an efficiency play."\par \par \uc2 Companies that own their servers and store them in-house may be using as little as 20 per cent of the capacity available at any given time or have peaks and troughs of usage. Having another company host the server, which can then be used by other clients increases the efficiency of each server, removes the initial outlay and maintenance costs, and potentially raises the utilization rate to nearly 80 per cent.\par \par \uc2 "A key opportunity for business to achieve their green and CSR [\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ] commitments is focused on how well and efficiently they use data centres," says Andrew Halliwell, director of commercial development at \uc2 Cable & Wireless\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Mr Halliwell says regulatory initiatives such as the Carbon Reduction Commitment in the UK are also making companies think more carefully about how they can be greener and save money at the same time.\par \par \uc2 Gartner estimates that the cloud computing market will be worth $68.3bn by the end of 2010, a near 17 per cent rise on last year. It says that there has been "an acceleration of adoption of cloud computing and cloud services among enterprises and an explosion of supply-side activity as technology providers maneuver to exploit the growing commercial opportunity."\par \par \uc2 Mr Halliwell says that start-up companies have been among the early adopters of the move into the cloud because it saves them investment in expensive server equipment from the outset. Companies that are in the process of merging have also looked to the cloud as a way of bringing together competing systems on the same platform.\par \par \uc2 However, some cloud providers admit that financial services companies remain more reluctant to make the shift because of concerns over security and issues over sharing their physical server with a potential rival.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, analysts say there is a further role for technology companies to play in driving the green agenda.\par \par \uc2 Warren Wilson, senior analyst at Ovum, says that "to make a real difference, you need to tackle the big sources of carbon emissions" such as manufacturing industries. He says the use of IT in these cases will ultimately have a far bigger impact on the carbon footprint than simply reducing the amount of power and water used by data centres.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 goog : \uc2 Google Inc.\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i163 : \uc2 Electric Power Generation - Alternative Energy | i8395466 : \uc2 Data Processing Services | i1 : \uc2 Energy | i16 : \uc2 Electricity/Gas Utilities | i16101 : \uc2 Electric Power Generation | ibcs : \uc2 Business/Consumer Services | ieutil : \uc2 Electric Utilities | 