l\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 On Wednesday, I wondered why I had a new burst of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://twitter.com/revkin"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 followers on Twitter}}}\uc2 . Then I noticed that {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://twitter.com/leodicaprio"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Leonardo DiCaprio}}}\uc2  had re-tweeted my recent suggestion that Apple, which has long named its Macintosh operating systems for the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/28/technology/circuits/28pogue.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 tiger}}}\uc2  and other {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/27/technology/personaltech/27pogue.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 wild cats}}}\uc2 , help conserve the world's last few dozen havens for wild tigers. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://wwf.panda.org/wwf_news/?196791/DiCaprio-If-we-save-the-tigers-well-save-the-planet"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 DiCaprio has been working with WWF}}}\uc2  (known as the World Wildlife Fund in the United States) to build support for tiger conservation.\par \par \uc2 What do you think Steve Jobs?Imagine what you can do to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/search/%2523SaveTheTigers"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 #SaveTheTigers}}}\uc2  with @{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/Revkin"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Revkin}}}\uc2 's idea: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://j.mp/ApplTig"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 http://j.mp/ApplTig}}}\par \par \uc2 - Leonardo DiCaprio (@LeoDiCaprio) {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/LeoDiCaprio/status/5050268290912256"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 November 18, 2010}}}\par \par \uc2 DiCaprio spread the word just ahead of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.globaltigerinitiative.org/2010/11/16/st-petersburg-tiger-summit/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 international summit on tiger conservation}}}\uc2  that is beginning today in St. Petersburg, Russia, and because a recent {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/09/15/saving-wild-tigers-cheaply-with-apples-help/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 study concluded that safeguarding tiger habitat}}}\uc2  could be done at a very modest cost. There is an urgent need for such an initiative. Only about 2,500 adult breeding tigers persist in the wild and habitat has been rapidly eroding in the past decade. Earlier this month, Traffic, a network monitoring poaching and commerce in rare wildlife, released "{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.traffic.org/home/2010/11/9/more-than-1000-tigers-reduced-to-skin-and-bones-in-last-deca.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Reduced to Skin and Bones}}}\uc2 ," a report finding skins, bone and other body parts from more than 1,000 tigers confiscated in 11 countries in the last decade.\par \par \uc2 The notion of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/topics/reference/timestopics/people/j/steven_p_jobs/index.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Steven Jobs}}}\uc2  and Apple giving something back to the great cats that are such appealing icons first surfaced on Dot Earth last year, thanks to a reader, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://bit.ly/AppleCats"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Jamie from Seattle}}}\uc2 , who {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/01/should-apple-help-save-leopards/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 broached the idea}}}\uc2  after seeing a snow leopard photograph from Afghanistan.\par \par \uc2 I ran this by Apple's press office and on Friday was told that the company had {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://twitter.com/#!/Revkin/status/5732203904372736"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 no response for DiCaprio or Dot Earth}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The company, of course, is free to be as parsimonious as it, its shareholders and board of directors want it to be. Customers and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://philanthropy.com/blogs/social-philanthropy/is-apple-anti-charity/24565"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 charities}}}\uc2  have complained about a lack of focus on philanthropy by the company or\u160\'00\'A0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wired.com/gadgets/mac/commentary/cultofmac/2006/01/70072"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 its leader}}}\uc2 . But Apple's attitude on this question does stand in sharp contrast to that of other prominent and profitable companies. For instance, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/exxon_mobil_corporation/index.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Exxon Mobil}}}\uc2 , which starting in 1959 encouraged drivers to "{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.exxonmobil.com/Corporate/history/images/timeline/1959.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 put a tiger in your tank}}}\uc2 ," has {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.exxonmobil.com/Corporate/energy_env_biodiversity_inv_savetiger.aspx"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 donated more than $15 million}}}\uc2  since 1995 to the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.savethetigerfund.org/AM/Template.cfm?Section=Home1"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Save the Tiger Fund}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Apple, of course, isn't the only company profiting from the image of mighty felines, including the tiger. I have a query in to the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.kelloggcompany.com/company.aspx?id=888"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Kellogg Corporation}}}\uc2 , as well, given its longtime use of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.frostedflakes.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Tony the Tiger}}}\uc2  to sell Frosted Flakes. [Kellogg Corporation sent a response on Monday, appended below.]\par \par \uc2 I noticed that the company has been very aggressive about {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.brandchannel.com/home/post/2010/07/23/Tony-the-Tiger-Defends-Kelloggs.aspx"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 protecting the trademarks it holds on the tiger character}}}\uc2 . Is it worth investing in protecting the real thing, too?\par \par \uc2 If you're an Apple shareholder, or Mac owner, would you see the merit in helping sustain the wildlife that build the image of the products you use?\par \par \uc2 [6:12 p.m. | Updated The Kellogg press office sent this response Monday night from Tim Knowlton, vice president for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 :\par \par \uc2 Thank you for your inquiry. At Kellogg, we work to leverage our financial resources, work force talents and brands to support the communities in which we operate, as well as the global community overall. In 2009, we contributed more than $9 million in cash and $22 million in products to nonprofits and charitable organizations worldwide . As a part of this, we provide a dollar-for-dollar match of grants made by employees to organizations seeking to improve and protect the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including endangered species. In recent years, this matching program has resulted in grants to organizations that protect tigers.]\par \par \uc2 [*An observant reader noticed that the initial headline, "DiCaprio Presses Apple to Aid Wild Tigers," could be read two ways, one of which implied the movie star was making cider to save tigers. The perils of Sunday morning posting. ]\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/11/24/wild-tigers-on-a-crowding-planet/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Wild Tigers on a Crowding Planet}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/11/22/the-next-ailing-wild-cat-in-apples-software-pipeline/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 The Next Ailing Wild Cat in Apple's Software Pipeline}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "