ute by email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The tabular content relating to this article is not available to view. Apologies in advance for the inconvenience caused.\par \par \uc2 One of the books that has influenced my thinking on business is Religion and the Rise of Capitalism (1926) by R.H. Tawney, the British economic historian and social critic, whose most important work was done in the inter-war period. In this book, perhaps his most famous work, he traces the church's attitude towards profit, and how that changed over time - how we moved from an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  when even the morality of a small amount of profit was questioned to one where the unbridled pursuit of profits, if legally obtained, is celebrated.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The larger point he makes is that the complex forces that led to the separation of church and commerce, of social responsibility and shareholder value maximisation, while beneficial in many ways, may have gone too far.\par \par \uc2 Shareholder value maximisation is mistakenly caricatured today as naked greed - in fact, much of what passes as \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , such as doing good for the community in which you do business, could be seen as part of long-run shareholder value maximisation.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, the principle of shareholder value maximisation does encourage management to leave issues of morality and politics to the shareholders, while keeping management's focus on making money. Is this always an appropriate separation of realms? The appropriate dictum for management will be debated vigorously in coming years, and this book offers a good starting point for reflection.\par \par \uc2 The writer is professor of finance at the University of Chicago Booth School of Business.\par \par \uc2 ......................................\par \par \uc2 "All literature is about sex," my English professor at Cambridge told me as an undergraduate. He should have added it is also about money. For me, there are two books whose views on money hold the greatest relevance to business today.\par \par \uc2 F. Scott Fitzgerald's The Great Gatsby is the story of a man who knows the only way to capture his lover's heart is to become rich - he describes the appeal of wealth and his lover: "Her voice sounded of money." No matter if he gains his wealth in a Bernie Madoff way.\par \par \uc2 But even when Gatsby becomes rich, he's still a tragic outsider. Fitzgerald makes the point that some clubs just can't be crashed with what I find to be the most appalling - but true - line in the book. "Tom and Daisy - they smashed up things and creatures and then retreated back into their money or their vast carelessness, or whatever it was that kept them together, and let other people clean up the mess they had made."\par \par \uc2 As I write I think of several fund managers who lost their clients millions in the crash of 2008 - but they still have their planes, boats and palaces.\par \par \uc2 But it was Truman Capote's In Cold Blood, the true-life thriller, that taught me the most about the pursuit of money.\par \par \uc2 I stayed up all night reading the book, desperate to unravel the psychological motives behind the appalling murders of the Clutter family. I was sure it had to be something shocking, surprising, exotic. But then comes the awful, bland truth - six people died because one dark night men went looking for a safe full of money and found nothing.\par \par \uc2 The motive for the crime hangs on just one paragraph, when Perry Smith, one of the killers, empties the purse of the 12-year-old Nancy Clutter. "I found a little purse - like a doll's purse. Inside it was a silver dollar. I dropped it . . . and I had to get down on my knees . . . it made me sick . . . here I am on my knees crawling on my belly to steal a child's silver dollar."\par \par \uc2 The disgust within Smith leads to the sickening killings - and right there, on the page laid out in Capote's cold clinical style, you have it: the desperation, the longing and the extreme actions people will take - for money, or even worse the humiliation of the lack of it.\par \par \uc2 Fast forward to 2010. In Cold Blood explains Bernie Madoff and all those like him; it explains the desires that led to the financial crisis - and will lead to future crises. It does what great literature ought to do. It shows us reality in extremis, so that we just cannot disconnect it from it; we can never forget the true place of money in life. We can only wish that life were not like that.\par \par \uc2 The writer is a contributor to Vanity Fair magazine.\par \par \uc2 ......................................\par \par \uc2 I first learnt about the dark side of business from the 11-year-old eponymous protagonist of William Gaddis's 1975 National Book Award-winning novel, JR. That little boy was the ultimate capitalist, an absurdly youthful amalgam of history's great swindlers. I admired him as he flitted among business deals, trading navy surplus picnic forks, defaulted bonds and natural gas rights. Between sixth-grade classes, he bought and broke up a textile business, laid off workers, executed a complex sale-leaseback, leveraged a pension fund, extracted tax credits and then, finally, used accounting gimmickry to swap what was left over for a brewery. I admired all of this.\par \par \uc2 But I also knew JR was doomed. When I saw my first trading floor, in the 1990s, my immediate thought was of JR working his school's public phone. And since I left Wall Street, my memory of JR has resurfaced many times: after Nick Leeson, or Bernie Madoff, or J\u233\'00\'E9r\u244\'00\'F4me Kerviel.\par \par \uc2 The parallels to today's schemes are eerie, and the book perfectly captures how fraudsters become trapped by their own dealings. JR exclaims: "I mean even when you win you have to keep playing!" What if the world's bankers had learnt that lesson at JR's age?\par \par \uc2 The writer is professor of law at the University of San Diego.\par \par \uc2 ......................................\par \par \uc2 Very rarely these days does anyone read the novels of the American writer John Phillips "JP" Marquand, and that is a shame. Marquand, who died in 1960, won the Pulitzer Prize in 1938 for The Late George Apley. But, for me, his masterpiece will always be Point of No Return, a 1949 gem about Charley Gray, who returns to New York City from serving in the second world war wondering what the true purpose of his life should be.\par \par \uc2 Would he be best served by staying put at his rolltop desk in a private Wall Street banking firm, or should he move back to his quaint New England town? Will he be promoted at the bank? How has his New England upbringing prepared him for his life in New York? How Gray grapples with these - and other - existential questions, under Marquand's authoritative hand, evolves into one of the more striking and thought-provoking financial novels ever written, a literary genre with a very rich history - see Theodore Dreiser and Anthony Trollope - that only very rarely gets served up any more for our enjoyment.\par \par \uc2 The writer is a former investment banker.\par \par \uc2 ......................................\par \par \uc2 The novel that has taught me the most about business and work is Belle du Seigneur, the 1930s masterpiece written in French by Swiss writer Albert Cohen. The first day I began work in a big company, 20 years ago, a colleague advised me to reread the novel. "You'll understand everything you need to know about the way it works here", he said.\par \par \uc2 He was right. Belle du Seigneur is a vast, astonishing book that has much relevance to the modern workplace, showing its hypocrisy, envy, machismo, conformity. We meet bigoted employees who speak a pompous jargon. It is an acid satire on the emptiness of middle-class existence, its worship of power and money.\par \par \uc2 However, this magnificent novel is also about a tortuous love story between Solal, the ostentatious son of the Chief Rabbi of Cephalonia and Ariane, a beautiful, blonde, Protestant aristocrat. Alas, as far as I am concerned, I have not managed to find a Prince Charming in big companies.\par \par \uc2 The writer is the author of Bonjour Paresse (Hello Laziness), which parodies corporate culture, and Tchao la France (Good Bye France).\par \par \uc2 ......................................\par \par \uc2 One of the books that has made the most impact on me as a businessman is the Chinese work Tao Te Ching by Lao Tzu. The title means "the classic book about Tao". It consists of 81 verses or chapters from the Chinese philosophical tradition and is dated 600 BC. The first time I read Tao was in 2001; I try to return to this book four to five times a year for a more thorough read.\par \par \uc2 Many of the book's lessons have given me much food for thought in my career. Among them are that one should focus rather than spread one's resources; reflect rather than make quick and hasty decisions; adopt simplicity and humility as opposed to a cocky approach.\par \par \uc2 The text requires attention and reflection in order to digest it fully. However, the payback is immense: pragmatic advice as well as philosophical insights.\par \par \uc2 The writer is a former director at the Swedish retailer.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i83101 : \uc2 Investment Banking | ibnk : \uc2 Banking/Credit | i814 : \uc2 Banking | i831 : \uc2 Financial Investments | iinv : \uc2 Investing/Securities\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gbook : \uc2 Books | grel : \uc2 Religion | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gcom : \uc2 Society/Community/Work | gent : \uc2 Arts/Entertainment\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx93