talt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Financial Times (FT.Com)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2011 The Financial Times Ltd. All rights reserved. Please do not cut and paste FT articles and redistribute by email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 After the Four Horsemen of the Corporate Apocalypse have bolted, society usually calls in the Four Hand-Wringers of the Messy Aftermath to shut the stable door: regulation, pay restraint, governance - and social responsibility.\par \par \uc2 That is what happened after the Enron and WorldCom scandals a decade ago. It is happening again in the wake of the financial crisis. But this time, what used to be known as social responsibility, sustainability or plain philanthropy comes in the apparently novel guise of "shared value" or "constructive capitalism".\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Shared value is a neologism promoted by Michael Porter and Mark Kramer. It got the full "Big Idea" cover treatment - complete with the fluorescent orange headline "How to fix capitalism" - in the first Harvard Business Review of this year. Umair Haque noisily touts constructive capitalism online and in his book, The New Capitalist Manifesto.\par \par \uc2 For all their differences in prose style - the first sober, the second frenetic - these theses have a similar thrust. They even cite some of the same examples: \uc2 Hindustan Unilever\uc2 's Shakti initiative for distributing its products through a network of poor female entrepreneurs in Indian villages; mobile phone-based methods to encourage micro-businesses in Kenya or Bangladesh; \uc2 Walmart\uc2 's efforts to minimise costs imposed on local communities. These companies are generating profits, in Mr Haque's words, "whose benefits accrue sustainably, authentically and meaningfully to people, communities, society, the natural world and future generations". Prof Porter and Mr Kramer make the even more radical claim that profits with a long-range social purpose represent "a higher form of capitalism".\par \par \uc2 Heady stuff. But is this higher form really that different from the self-interested variety that Milton Friedman backed when he wrote that "the social responsibility of business is to increase profits"?\par \par \uc2 Advocates believe shared value initiatives are knitting together social and commercial benefits more closely than traditional \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  programmes can. So \uc2 Nestl\u233\'00\'E9\uc2 's intensive support for local coffee regions in Latin America and Africa improves the reliability of supply to its Nespresso division and the income and \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the farmers. Beneficiaries, distant from the recent "failure" of western capitalism, will increasingly start to see companies as the motor for improvements in their standards of living. Confidence in local companies should then underpin more lasting, socially beneficial partnerships between the public and private sectors, reinforcing a virtuous circle.\par \par \uc2 What is more, big companies are not merely bolting these programmes on to their core businesses, according to Mr Kramer. They are changing their internal structure to accommodate cross-divisional shared-value initiatives and hiring people to run them who understand the social and the business challenges, not just one or the other. No wonder supporters of old-style CSR feel defensive.\par \par \uc2 But many of these initiatives are not that new - the Shakti project is older than \uc2 Facebook\uc2  - and the impetus behind them isn't either. Prof Porter and Mr Kramer urge companies to see their decisions "through the shared-value lens". But business leaders must still calculate if a new market or a new way of sourcing will improve efficiency, productivity and profitability, whether the new market consists of poor villagers rather than wealthy yuppies or the new supplier is round the corner rather than halfway around the world.\par \par \uc2 The pursuit of shared value - or what Mr Haque calls "thick value" - plainly cannot eliminate the greed, excessive risk and bubbles that caused the Enron scandals and, later, the financial crisis. Constructive capitalists are still capitalists. Like all markets, these new ones will eventually become subject to diminishing returns. At that point most investors will choose the higher return available elsewhere, even if it yields the "wrong kind of profit".\par \par \uc2 In her 2009 book SuperCorp, which prefigured some of these more recent ideas, Rosabeth Moss Kanter warned of the pitfalls for companies that make "social commitments that do not have an economic logic that sustains the enterprise by attracting resources".\par \par \uc2 More companies are learning to reap commercial benefits from strategies that have a wider social value. That's great. But the basic job of coaxing capitalism in the right direction is the same as it always has been: find ways to harness society's needs to companies' self-interest and hope the two stay together.\par \par \uc2 andrew.hill@ft.com\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\