 \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Interview\par \par \uc2 Peter Woicke\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Charis Gresser hears how the former \uc2 JP Morgan\uc2  executive wanted to 'give something back' - but at first found life on the other side to be alien\par \par \uc2 Peter Woicke\uc2 's enthusiasm is palpable. Having had so much fun in both the private and public sectors, he says he is more than happy to reflect on his own moves between the two.\par \par \uc2 After three decades at \uc2 JP Morgan\uc2 , where he became member of the executive management group, Mr Woicke, a native German, left the bank in 1998.\par \par \uc2 The following year, he became chief executive of the \uc2 International Finance Corporation\uc2  (IFC) and managing director of the World Bank, where he stayed until his retirement in 2005. He then spent two years as chairman of the International Save the Children Alliance.\par \par \uc2 Mr Woicke, 68, is currently a board member of \uc2 Anglo American\uc2  and \uc2 Saudi Aramco\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 He explains how his big move from banking to development came about: "I really wanted to do something completely different. I wanted to leave the private sector. They had rewarded us very well. I thought it was good to give something back, something for society, something different from the overriding focus on shareholder value."\par \par \uc2 What he found, when he took the plunge and joined the IFC, was quite a shock. In retrospect, he says, he had a fantastic time, but he is also candid about the culture clash.\par \par \uc2 "First of all, I was shocked by the bureaucracy and the hierarchy. People felt they had to put their hand up in a meeting before they expressed an opinion... It took a while to convince people in meetings they could disagree with me without repercussions; that open dialogue would foster a better atmosphere."\par \par \uc2 He had been warned. A colleague he called when he was offered the job had said to him: "You will hate it. It's such a bureaucratic organisation...On second thoughts, since you will be sitting on top of the bureaucracy, it will be a great job."\par \par \uc2 The reality, of course, was more complex. As Mr Woicke argues, you cannot just streamline a bureaucracy through force of will: "You can't just dictate, you have to show there are better ways."\par \par \uc2 Bureaucracy aside, in the IFC Mr Woicke also found an organisation staffed with people who were passionate and proud of what they were doing, if at times they were also relatively risk averse compared with the world of banking.\par \par \uc2 On a personal level, he recalls at times coming across resistance because of his Wall Street background. In fact, his career at \uc2 JP Morgan\uc2  had given him some preparation for the world of development through postings which included Beirut, Rio de Janeiro and Singapore.\par \par \uc2 At the helm of the IFC, Mr Woicke describes an exhilarating time of change on many levels. Culturally, one of his biggest challenges was to speed up the process of making investment decisions.\par \par \uc2 Then there was the small matter of redefining the IFC's development role. By 2000, Mr Woicke realised that the IFC's traditional corporate clients no longer needed its support to invest in developing countries. The IFC embarked on a profound shift: moving many of its people from Washington to developing countries and providing direct support to companies in those countries.\par \par \uc2 Along the way, Mr Woicke became an early proponent of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It was there in embryonic form at the IFC more than a decade ago as a department focused on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and community relations.\par \par \uc2 He realised then what an important differentiator this could be for business: "We worked very hard at this, we improved the standards. It was very satisfying. We did a study that showed that clients that adhered to these standards had improved long-term profitability."\par \par \uc2 He was on the right side of history, for as he points out: "Today, CSR has the commitment of boards. Four or five years ago, it was still a struggle. Now, if we want to be successful, we have to put this in every investment decision we are making."\par \par \uc2 This profound change in the way companies view their social responsibilities means there is now greater scope for people's careers to span the public and private sector. "Now, if you are a specialist on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  or community relations in the public sector, you are in demand in private institutions," says Mr Woicke.\par \par \uc2 It is an evolution that he has seen first-hand. In the 1980s, when he was still at \uc2 JP Morgan\uc2 , Mr Woicke was once described as a communist for daring to worry out loud about the income inequality in Brazil.\par \par \uc2 When he went back in 2001, he says he was struck by the country's change, and the awareness he found among business people that vast gaps between rich and poor risked political instability, which in turn risked pushing up the cost of capital.\par \par \uc2 In another example of coming full circle, Mr Woicke recalls a disagreement at the IFC over the role of private education in Africa. A decade on, he shows with pride his business card as chair of the trustees of the Ashesi University Foundation, as he describes the progress of Ashesi University College, a private, not-for-profit institution in Ghana.\par \par \uc2 The private and public sectors may still have their own distinctive cultures, but, as Mr Woicke points out, each offers something to the other.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 aramco : \uc2 Saudi Arabian Oil Co | ifc : \uc2 International Finance Corp | cnyc : \uc2 JPMorgan Chase & Co.\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i83101 : \uc2 Investment Banking | ibnk : \uc2 Banking/Credit | i814 : \uc2 Banking | i831 : \uc2 Financial Investments | iinv : \uc2 Investing/Securities | i1 : \uc2 Energy | i13 : \uc2 Crude Oil/Natural Gas | i8150106 : \uc2 Development Banking\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0