and redistribute by email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 One of the first multinational executives to push for ethical business practices and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  was Sir Geoffrey Chandler, a director of Shell. It was the 1970s and often he faced the disdain of his peers, yet he insisted that companies had a moral responsibility to make human rights and protection of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  as much part of their bottom line as profit.\par \par \uc2 Strongly influenced by his father, a leading physician at Bart's hospital in London, Chandler believed business leaders should see themselves as having their own version of a Hippocratic Oath - a pledge "never to harm". That belief was strengthened by what he witnessed as an armed British secret agent behind Nazi lines in the second world war. With his life on the line, as an agent of Winston Churchill's Special Operations Executive, he helped provide weapons, cash and gold to Greek partisans, only to see left and rightwing factions fighting each other as much as their Nazi occupiers.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Years later, Chandler's principles led him and while at Shell in 1976 he introduced what he called a statement of general business principles, pledging the company to show corporate social and environmental responsibility. This was long before the idea became fashionable or politically correct and progress was painfully slow.\par \par \uc2 Shell itself and other multinationals were often in breach of such guidelines but gradually they have become the norm. Chandler took pride in seeing ethical business challenge the traditional idea of profit for profit's sake. Shell has since set up a global, internet-based facility for whistleblowers to report illegal or unethical business practises within the company.\par \par \uc2 Chandler's influence on Shell and beyond was because he was not a disillusioned employee but a senior executive with the accompanying credibility and clout. Here was an unabashed stalwart of capitalism saying that profit was not the be-all and end-all. "I don't believe ethical behaviour should depend on its paying," he once said. "To suggest that doing right needs to be justified by its economic reward is amoral, a self-inflicted wound hugely damaging to corporate reputation. Doing right because it is right needs to be the foundation of business."\par \par \uc2 Yet Chandler had little patience with human rights groups, non-governmental organisations or others who entrenched themselves in the traditional confrontation with business, rather than dialogue and engagement. Ethical business, he insisted, was a two-way street.\par \par \uc2 Chandler was a man whose experience and interests went beyond business. After the war he worked in broadcasting and spent five years working for the Financial Times before joining Shell where he stayed for more than 20 years. Then, in 1978, James Callaghan, Labour Prime Minister, asked him to become director general of the National Economic Development Office - known as "Neddy". The job, which he kept when Margaret Thatcher came to power, required considerable finesse as he sought to bridge differences between government, business and trade unions. In 1986, the Royal Society for the encouragement of the Arts, Manufactures and Commerce appointed him director of Industry 1986, an initiative designed to highlight the decline in UK manufacturing. Highlight it he did, though reversing the decline was beyond his powers or even those of Lady Thatcher.\par \par \uc2 Later he founded and chaired Amnesty International's UK Business and Human Rights Group, which encouraged companies to improve their human rights records, notably at the bottom of the supply-chain in "sweat shops" and cases of child labour. Although he formally stepped down in 2001 he remained a "towering figure" within Amnesty for the rest of his life, according to its UK director Kate Allen.\par \par \uc2 Born in London in 1922, Chandler was educated at Sherborne school in Dorset and Trinity College, Cambridge. At the age of 19, with the second world war raging, he joined the King's Royal Rifle Corps, where he became a captain before being assigned to Force 133 within the SOE, nicknamed "the Ministry of Ungentlemanly Warfare". There he met the now-legendary SOE agent and travel writer Patrick Leigh Fermor.\par \par \uc2 "The last time I saw Paddy was in Alexandria towards the end of the war when he and I were loading a jeep onto a ca\u239\'00\'EFque (a Greek fishing boat) athwartships," Chandler once told a friend. "The jeep was full of gold coins to pay off the partisans." Chandler was parachuted behind Nazi lines as a saboteur in Greece, where he learnt fluent Greek. He related his experiences in his book The Divided Land: an Anglo-Greek Tragedy, published in 1959. In it he criticised Britain for not imposing the rule of law in Greece after the defeat of the Nazis. A rightwing backlash to communist atrocities after the war resulted in bloody civil conflict in Greece.\par \par \uc2 After the war, Chandler remained in Greece as a British press and information officer, when he pushed for aid for the war-stricken Greek population. He returned to London to work for the BBC External Services in 1949 before joining the Financial Times as leader writer and features editor. In 1955, he married Lucy Buxton, a Quaker.\par \par \uc2 Joining the \uc2 Royal Dutch Shell\uc2  group in 1957, Chandler served as director of Shell Petroleum, Shell Petroleum NV and \uc2 Shell International\uc2  - often working in West Africa and the Caribbean. His Caribbean s\u233\'00\'E9jour led to him writing a highly respected guide to the butterflies of Trinidad. Butterflies, and gardening at his home in the village of Newdigate, Surrey, were among his great passions.\par \par \uc2 Sir Geoffrey, who was knighted in 1983, is survived by Lucy and their daughters Hilary, Sarah, Clare and Susan.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i951 : \uc2 Health Care\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Re