by email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Two recent events in Asia will put greater emphasis on environmental, social and governance issues, and socially responsible investing more generally. The first was the March earthquake and tsunami tragedy in Japan. In the wake of the nuclear disaster at the Fukushima power plant more investors can be expected to consider ESG criteria and companies will focus more intensely on how they communicate with shareholders.\par \par \uc2 The second event was the March announcement by China of the country's 12th five-year economic plan. The details include a number of explicit references to environmental and social factors. The country's leadership has now set objectives that target the quality and not just the absolute level of economic growth that has dominated previous plans.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Socially responsible investing in Japan can trace its roots back to the formation of the Valdez society that adopted a 10-point code of corporate environmental conduct in 1992 and was named after the Exxon Valdez, the oil tanker that ran aground in Alaska in 1989.\par \par \uc2 The first publicly offered SRI mutual fund in Japan was launched in 1999 and was followed by many similarly invested funds that captured the growing public awareness of environmental issues. Unfortunately these funds suffered in the stock market fall following the bursting of the technology bubble and regained popularity in the subsequent recovery from 2003, at which time a number of new funds were launched. As at the end of 2010 there were more than 80 such funds in Japan with total assets of $5.4bn, representing 0.7 per cent of the mutual fund market.\par \par \uc2 In contrast, interest among pension funds, universities and other public bodies in Japan has remained small, although many are paying attention to the UN Principles for Responsible Investment. It is interesting to note that one of the early shareholder activist groups was the Tepco Anti-Nuclear Shareholder's Group, formed in 1989.\par \par \uc2 China has a social and environmental set of objectives as it seeks to rebalance its economy away from dependency on exports with a focus on sustainability. The latest five-year plan aims to reduce carbon emissions by 17 per cent by 2015 and the government will introduce tax incentives for energy conservation and emission reduction.\par \par \uc2 The leading national bank ICBC announced concurrently that it is to double lending to companies in this sector - bank lending in China is very much driven by official policy. Electric vehicles are highlighted as a strategic industry as part of the five-year plan and climate change features prominently. There are targets for non-fossil energy and forests. Social issues are also addressed and the plan aims to increase the minimum wage by more than 80 per cent from current levels as part of several measures aimed at addressing income disparity.\par \par \uc2 According to the Association for Sustainable and Responsible Investment in Asia, established in 2001, there are some 419 SRI funds available to investors across the region including Japan (including 158 that are faith based).\par \par \uc2 In 2009 Asria published a report sponsored by the Asian Development Bank encouraging Asia's government pension funds to lead a shift towards responsible investing and emulate similar moves in North America and Europe. The report states that most Asian government pension funds are lagging behind in their adoption of ESG strategies and encourages the use of proxy voting to apply pressure for greater corporate disclosure. Asria has this year published two reports on climate change from an investment perspective.\par \par \uc2 Other institutional investors in Asia have typically viewed responsible investing as a European or US approach, and instead focus on their fiduciary responsibility to meet the investment objectives that match their liabilities. In the absence of research that states unequivocally that responsible investing performs better over time or limits the downside, the pragmatism of most Asian institutions to focus on performance has prevailed.\par \par \uc2 However, the growing interest in the approach, that will likely be given more attention as a result of recent events, can be evidenced by increasing amounts of sell-side research. Both \uc2 Goldman Sachs\uc2  and CLSA, the Asian equity broker, are producing regular studies. CLSA concludes in a recent report that companies exercising higher \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  standards have marginally outperformed those that are lagging in the practice. The report encourages investors to focus on supply chains and to consider the working conditions of Asian workplaces, stating that it is all about the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and labour standards.\par \par \uc2 In a report from last year, \uc2 Goldman Sachs\uc2  says Chinese companies have potential to sustain industry leadership by integrating ESG factors as they make the transition from being cost leaders to innovators. This is aligned with the objectives of the current five-year plan.\par \par \uc2 Whether this growing interest in responsible investing encourages more mutual funds to be launched remains to be seen.\par \par \uc2 At the least the region's institutional investors will need to pay the issue more attention and fund managers will be increasingly integrating ESG criteria as part of their investment process.\par \par \uc2 Mark Konyn is chief executive of RCM Asia Pacific, a company of Allianz Global Investors\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 iresinv : \uc2 Responsible Investing | i16101 : \uc2 Electric Power Generation | i1 : \uc2 Energy | i16 : \uc2 Electricity/Gas Utilities | i81502 : \uc2 Trusts/Funds/Financial Vehicles | ialtinv : \uc2 Alternative Investments | ieutil : \uc2 Electric Utilities | iinv : \uc2 Investing/Securities\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | e1101 : \uc2 Economic Growth | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | e11 : \uc2