edistribute by email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The Business in the Community Corporate Responsibility Index was designed to identify new, emerging trends among early adopters. The latest results reveal that organisations are starting to link executive bonuses to the achievement of responsible business targets. This promotes the importance of corporate responsibility and assists in embedding its practices throughout the business.\par \par \uc2 The index shows an increase from 52 per cent in 2009 to 66 per cent in the number of companies reporting connecting corporate responsibility factors with bonus and remuneration systems. High CR Index scorers can show that board members and senior managers are incentivised for carrying forward the sustainability commitments made by the business.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "The perception of society is that the days of large, short-term financially based bonuses are gone," says Patrick Mallon, field director at Business in the Community.\par \par \uc2 "People want to see reward tied to the long-term sustainable success of the business. It must be based on a balancing act between what you do, in terms of creating short-term value, and how you go about it, by adhering to the values of the organisation. It is not a panacea and there is still some way to go."\par \par \uc2 The leading-edge organisations are moving away from treating corporate responsibility as an issue that is separate from core business strategy and operations.\par \par \uc2 CR is no longer a "useful but dispensable" add-on to "real" business activities. It is being integrated into the organisations' daily processes, becoming less visible as it becomes part of everybody's daily activities. Most employees have busy workloads, but if it affects their reward it can no longer be relegated below other objectives for which they are judged and rewarded.\par \par \uc2 The Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development has not yet picked up this trend. However, Charles Cotton, its reward adviser, can clearly see the current disconnect. Organisations are saying the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  is important, and are reporting the actions they are taking, but it is not backed up by bonuses or appraisal systems.\par \par \uc2 "At the moment there is a disconnect between CSR [\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ] and HR [human resources]," he says. "If an organisation values corporate responsibility, then it should be reflected in how it rewards and recognises people. If not, it may just be something that the public affairs department has come up with."\par \par \uc2 He gives organisations the benefit of the doubt, in that they have been focusing on dealing with the impacts of the economic downturn. When the economy starts to recover, he expects organisations to take a wider focus. "When they do, they must not restrict it to the executive level," he advises. "They must also change the attitudes and behaviours of rank-and-file employees."\par \par \uc2 Tesco is one company that is leading the way in this area. Its core purpose and values are the foundation of a balanced scorecard, which drives the day-to-day management of the business and prioritises its key issues. It consists of five segments: community, operations, people, finance and customer. Every year, performance targets are set against each of the segments.\par \par \uc2 "'Community' is the Tesco term for what others call 'corporate responsibility' or 'sustainability'," explains Lucy Neville-Rolfe, the company's corporate and legal affairs executive. "It is very motivating for everyone who works here that we include community and climate change targets in our performance framework. It is good for Tesco and good for society."\par \par \uc2 For example, store managers report on carbon reduction targets, as well as community initiatives. The bonuses of executive directors on the board are linked to the company's corporate responsibility performance. "Inclusion of community and climate change targets in our performance framework is one of the things that differentiates Tesco," says Ms Neville-Rolfe.\par \par \uc2 Centrica\uc2  is another early adopter. In 2009 it linked health, safety and environmental performance to the bonuses of senior management, including executives, as part of its annual incentive scheme. This scheme affects about 13 per cent of employees and in 2010 progress against target performance affected about 10 per cent of employee bonuses.\par \par \uc2 Employees are assessed against the trend of key performance indicators over the year towards targets, as well as comparison with 2009 performance. "This approach will continue in 2011," says Briana Whitlock in the company's \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  team. "Good performance in these areas is crucial to meeting our business priorities and we need to ensure that meeting our targets is a top priority."\par \par \uc2 Mr Mallon says senior executives he talks to are increasingly interested in their legacy, not just their short-term financial performance. This is not just the influence they have had on the business itself, but how their organisation has influenced society in general and the natural \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . He expects to see this attitude grow over time.\par \par \uc2 The recent public outcry against large bonuses based on short-term financial performance should be a catalyst for the inclusion of long-term CSR targets into bonus and appraisal systems at all levels.\par \par \uc2 This is a trend that continues other long standing initiatives, such as Tomorrow's Company, which believes that believe that business can and must be a "force for good".\par \par \uc2 There is also integrated accounting, which demonstrates the linkages between an organisation's strategy, governance and financial performance and the social, environmental and economic context within which it operates and the triple bottom line, which encourages reporting financial, people and environmental profit and loss.\par \par \uc2 "What will distinguish the quality of management at the most senior level in businesses in the future," concludes Mr Mallon, "is ability to manage and respond to short-term pressure, whilst at the same time 'steering the ship' over the longer term."\par \par \uc2 ..................................................\par \par \uc2 CASE STUDY: \uc2 Marks and Spencer\par \par \uc2 Marks and Spencer\uc2  launched Plan A, its sustainability plan, in 2007. Sustainability objectives were already embedded in middle management performance reviews, all the way down to store managers, who are assessed on areas such as energy, waste, carrier-bag usage and coat-hanger reuse. Shop floor staff have separate contributory objectives.\par \par \uc2 However, at a series of stakeholder meetings, the audience consistently asked when sustainability performance would be extended to senior management and board bonuses. "They said that Plan A is really great, the board is committed to it and it influences staff bonuses, but why isn't the board bonused," says Rowland Hill, the company's sustainability development manager? "Lifting it up to the board was the last piece of the jigsaw."\par \par \uc2 A formal scheme was developed for directors and senior management which started in the third year of Plan A. Three quarters of their bonus is based on corporate and divisional financial performance and one-quarter on personal objectives. Of this, one-fifth, amounting to 5 per cent of the total bonus, is based on personal achievements towards Plan A. The scheme is now in its second year.\par \par \uc2 "It seems to be about the right sort of level," says Mr Hill. "Five per cent is enough to get people's attention to take a very personal interest. It is also a good way to ensure that it is cascaded down through their team."\par \par \uc2 The company has achieved 95 of the 180 Plan A commitments so far, with a net benefit of more than \u163\'00\'A370m ($114m).\par \par \uc2 All those in the scheme received their full bonus in its first year, but Mr Hill says they had to work very hard to achieve it, as the easier commitments had already been met in the first two years. The first year of the bonus, therefore, coincided with addressing more challenging commitments. In particular, it has encouraged directors and senior managers to seek additional capital funds, especially for renewable energy and energy efficiency.\par \par \uc2 "We have continued to make good progress on Plan A," says Mr Hill. "There is no doubt that when things got more challenging, three years in the link to remuneration encouraged both management focus and investment."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15