\lin0 \uc2 Corporate responsibility is not new and many businesses have been doing great work in their local communities for many years. The government wants to see more businesses taking a real interest in the communities they serve by taking part in "Every Business Commits".\par \par \uc2 As part of the Big Society our ambition is to put more power and opportunity into people's hands. It is about giving citizens, communities and business the power they need to come together to solve problems that are important to them and to help build the Britain they want.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 These solutions are often better if they come from communities and businesses themselves, and this is where the Big Society meets the government's localism agenda. Government can help by setting the right economic conditions and \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  but communities are more empowered to decide what works for them.\par \par \uc2 Corporate responsibility is at the heart of business playing its role in a Big Society and "Every Business Commits" is a simple framework which provides a focus around five key priorities where business can, and already is, making a real difference.\par \par \uc2 We are committed to creating a stable economy, with lower taxation and less regulation.\par \par \uc2 We are also investing in the skills needed so that employers can get the employees with the right skills by, for example, investing an extra \u163\'00\'A3180m for an extra 50,000 apprentices. Getting involved with the push for new apprenticeships and our drive to help the young unemployed is one practical example of business playing its Big Society role.\par \par \uc2 There is no prescription here - the precise contribution of each business will be different - but we do have clear strategic priorities: we want businesses to invest in skills and jobs, enterprise, carbon reduction, employee health and well-being and supporting communities.\par \par \uc2 We think businesses won't do this just because government is asking them to. They will do it because it makes real business sense. There is growing evidence that being responsible can bring real commercial benefits.\par \par \uc2 For example, consumers increasingly value ethically produced and fairly traded products, jobseekers will challenge their prospective employers on their social and environmental commitments; and investors increasingly see \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  as integral to effective corporate strategy.\par \par \uc2 I want to champion the belief that businesses can do well and prosper while making a positive contribution to society.\par \par \uc2 The national awards are one very good way of doing this. And I want to congratulate those companies demonstrating good practice but I also want businesses to spread the word and inspire every business to commit to some form of action on five strategic priorities.\par \par \uc2 I will look forward to meeting the winners at the Awards for Excellence Gala dinner in London on July 5. Edward Davey is minister for employment relations and Liberal Democrat MP for Kingston and Surbiton.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\int