spnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Santander Small Company of the Year\par \par \uc2 Maloney's Budgens\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The store group believes in keeping high streets sacred, writes Virginia Marsh\par \par \uc2 When Budgens hosted a family fun day last September to celebrate its 100 years on the high street in Ascot, Berkshire, the response was overwhelming: almost 2,000 people turned up, three to four times the number expected.\par \par \uc2 It was proof, says Vince Maloney, the owner, that "people want to be part of a community" - even in one of the plushest parts of London's often soulless commuter belt.\par \par \uc2 The event was the culmination of four years' hard work by Mr Maloney, 48, and his younger brother Dennis, 46, who bought the store in 2006 and subsequently two others in nearby Virginia Water and Shepperton.\par \par \uc2 Last year alone, despite the UK's difficult trading conditions, nearly 40 per cent of profits were ploughed back into community initiatives, resulting, in the words of the judges, in a "fantastic amount of involvement for the size of the organisation".\par \par \uc2 Maloney's Budgens has, among other things, helped new management teams turn around two previously failing primary schools, supported local producers, reinvigorated other businesses by reviving a local traders' association and introduced special services for disabled and elderly people.\par \par \uc2 On the business side, it has retrained its 135 staff, helping it retain more than two-thirds of full-time employees since the final store acqusition in 2008, against the 40-50 per cent that would be expected in the retail sector over that period. Turnover since then has risen 10 per cent, to about \u163\'00\'A313m a year, even though a new Tesco opened opposite the Ascot store last year. This hit the branch's sales by 10 per cent - half the usual decline in such circumstances.\par \par \uc2 Mr Maloney, then Budgens' national sales director, acquired the business after Musgrave, the Irish group behind the neighbourhood supermarket chain, decided to sell off corporate branches. Under a franchise-like system, Musgrave manages the group brand and supplies 95 per cent of a branch's stock but leaves independent operators to build their own local presence and small suppliers.\par \par \uc2 "We differentiate ourselves by working with the community," says Mr Maloney, a Londoner who now lives locally. "It all comes down to one thing - keeping village high streets sacred. We have seen what can happen when big supermarkets open on the edge of town."\par \par \uc2 On the personal side, he says involvement with local children is especially rewarding. While Ascot has a reputation for affluence, it also has a council estate. As well as fund-raising for the two schools it supports, Maloney's supplies free food to their breakfast and supper clubs and is sponsoring a children's cooking competition in the autumn.\par \par \uc2 He also singles out the Shepperton traders' association initiative, saying he had not expected its impact to have been so significant.\par \par \uc2 Looking ahead, he says it is crucial for other businesses to become more involved in their communities, especially given the scale of government cuts. He gives the example of a local charity that supplies Budgens' groceries to housebound elderly and disabled customers but has recently lost 90 per cent of its funding.\par \par \uc2 "Don't underestimate what you can do as a business in the community," he says. "There's much more beyond token money-giving."\par \par \uc2 Pachacuti, which imports Fair Trade Panama hats and clothing, was highly recommended for setting up with ethics at the heart of the business, as it aims to improve significantly the lives of the co-operative workers in the Andean region of South America who make the hats.\par \par \uc2 The other shortlisted companies in this category, with judges' comments, were: Logistik, a design and communications agency, for integrating \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  into the core of its business - from reducing waste, pollution and carbon emissions to looking after the workforce and local community; Phoenix Gas, a natural gas company based in Northern Ireland, for developing a wide-ranging CR programme, Phoenix Life. This includes health and wellbeing programmes for staff, community initiatives and a comprehensive \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  strategy.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c1512 : \uc2 Dividends | c15 : \uc2 Performance | c151 : \uc2 Earnings | cactio : \uc2 Corporate Actions | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfce : \uc2 FC&E Exclusion Filter | nfcpin : \uc2 FC&E Industry News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\cl