or the ambiguous odor, the unshaken bees attempted to sample it 40% of the time, but the shaken bees did so less than 10% of the time, apparently fearing a mouthful of bitter. Their levels of several neurotransmitters also dropped.\par \par \uc2 Rats and dogs showing such behavior after stress are called anxious or depressed. Bees may have a similar state of mind, despite their tiny brains, the researchers said.\par \par \uc2 "Agitated Honeybees Exhibit Pessimistic Cognitive Biases," Current Biology, Melissa Bateson, Suzanne Desire, Sarah E. Gartside and Geraldine A. Wright, Current Biology (June 21)\par \par \uc2 PSYCHOLOGY\par \par \uc2 'Boy' and 'Girl' Numbers\par \par \uc2 The Greek mathematician Pythagoras believed that odd numbers were male and even numbers were female. A new study has seemingly confirmed this view, at least as it applies to perception.\par \par \uc2 In one test, the researchers asked 74 Americans to rate the masculinity or femininity of 18 names on an eight-point scale. Half the participants rated the names alone, and the rest saw "1" or "2" in front of them. On average, participants rated the names as more feminine when they were linked with "2."\par \par \uc2 In a more direct measure, the same people rated 10 objects or concepts as masculine or feminine. On that list were "1," which was rated as masculine, and "2," rated as feminine.\par \par \uc2 In a related experiment, test subjects judged that babies of ambiguous gender were more likely to be male when their photographs appeared alongside three odd numbers than when they appeared alongside three even numbers.\par \par \uc2 "Are Numbers Gendered?," James E. B. Wilkie and Galen V. Bodenhausen, Journal of Experimental Psychology (forthcoming)\par \par \uc2 BUSINESS\par \par \uc2 Damage Control Inc.\par \par \uc2 A study suggests that a key reason companies do good works is to offset earlier wrongs or controversies.\par \par \uc2 The researchers looked at 15 years worth of information, through 2005, taken from the main reference work on corporate responsibility, the Social Ratings Database of KLD Research & Analytics. The database contains positive and negative judgments for more than 3,000 companies annually, on activities relating to the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , community relations, human rights, product safety and so on. It also notes whether companies made money from gambling, tobacco and other controversial wares.\par \par \uc2 Getting a negative score on the corporate-responsibility ledger one year predicted a positive score the next year, the researchers found. Bad behavior with respect to the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , human rights and community relations predicted subsequent good works in those same areas. Misdeeds in corporate governance also drove a lot of reform programs, though not in the area of corporate governance. Instead, the companies did good works in other fields, like the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "\b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  for Irresponsibility," Matthew J. Kotchen and Jon Jungbien Moon, NBER Working Paper (July)\par \par \uc2 ---\par \par \uc2 Forget the Finger Prick, Just Scan a Tattoo With Your iPhone\par \par \uc2 Researchers at Northeastern University are working on a "tattoo" that can monitor the wearer's glucose and sodium levels.\par \par \uc2 The monitor, which provides alerts about unhealthy fluctuations without the need to draw blood, could be a boon to diabetics, intense exercisers and others. Hundreds of thousands of tiny sensors, each 100 nanometers across, are injected into an area two millimeters wide, just under the skin. The sensors change shade (red for sodium, yellow for glucose) as they interact with the wearer's blood cells; an accurate reading requires bathing them in fluorescent rays. The researchers have created a prototype light that fits onto an iPhone; an app could then interpret the colors. The tattoos work with mice, but they have not yet been tested with human subjects.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.djreprints.com/link/DJRFactiva.html?FACTIVA=wjco20110806000044"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 License this article from Dow Jones Reprint Service}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c23 : \uc2 Research/Development | ccpgvn : \uc2 Corporate Governance/Investor Relations | genv : \uc2 Environmental News | ghea : \uc2 Health | gsci : \uc2 Science/Technology | c41 : \uc2 Management Issues | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpin : \uc2 FC&E Industry News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 usa : \uc2 United States | namz : \uc2 North America\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt