gaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2011 Dow Jones & Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved.  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Edited interview with \uc2 General Electric Co\uc2 . Chief Executive Jeff Immelt, conducted Aug. 30 in Fairfield, Conn., by The Wall Street Journal.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: What is the disconnect between achieving your strategic goals and the share price? And what are you doing to try to get investors to rethink how they see GE?\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Mr. Immelt: It's hard to give an answer without sounding defensive. When I look back, there are three or four things we wanted to do. We wanted to focus the portfolio, invest in technology, because you just can't get technology wrong; globalize the company; and I think sustain a good leadership team and culture. So I feel good about those things we've done inside the company, and I think in many ways I feel like the company is better positioned today.\par \par \uc2 The last 10 years have been a mess from a macro standpoint. I mean 9/11, Hurricane Katrina, the financial crisis, Fukushima. I mean, I could go down a list. Not that I want a crying towel, but the macro scene has been horrific. And in that process, we have gone from being a 40 or 50 P/E stock to\u8212\'20\'14if you look at analyst projections of 2012, we trade at 10 times 2012 earnings.\par \par \uc2 So I think it is rediscovering with investors the value of financial services. Clearly financial services have taken the biggest toll. The stock traded above $40 in 2007. The financial crisis hit, and GE was hard hit. I think it is rediscovering the value of \uc2 GE Capital\uc2  with our investors. We obviously think it is worth more than they do right now. I think that is only going to come with time and paying a dividend and things like that.\par \par \uc2 Our earnings over the next few years should perform well versus the S&P 500. We've got to let the results do the talking. I can't stand on my chair and cry. I think it is going to be about results, and it is going to be about what valuation investors think they can put on financial services.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Is \uc2 GE Capital\uc2  core to GE?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: We think so. I have to look at it over a broad time period. In the fall of 2008, it was a tough neighborhood. And I would say there are a lot of investors, even big investors, who today would prefer to see the company without it.\par \par \uc2 But if you look at it over a long period of time historically, it has been a good performer in the portfolio. More importantly, when I look forward in the future, we see some good competitive advantage. We think \uc2 GE Capital\uc2  is like 100 times safer than what it was. If you look at leverage, it is below 4 to 1. If you look at our share of the unsecured lending market, it is down.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Will you be narrowing the focus of the finance arm to support the industrial core?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: Narrowing the focus to primarily commercial finance. Verticals which really are aligned with our products. What we call commercial lending and leasing which are, what I would say, very GE-type businesses. These are businesses where we have scale advantages, even funding advantages versus banks and use lots of GE capability with retailers and industrial clients. So I think that is going to be big. And a much smaller commercial real-estate portfolio. And then we think we have got an advantage in what I would call specialty consumer franchise, which is the private-label credit card and retail. Those four areas are primarily the ones that we think are core to the company going forward.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: What size do you see \uc2 GE Capital\uc2  being going forward?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: We want it to be less than 40% of total earnings. We think that the size we talk about\u8212\'20\'14which is like $440 billion of net investment\u8212\'20\'14would make us like 2% of the commercial paper and long-term unsecured funding market. When I sit back and look out not just where we are this year, but where we are over the next four to five years, we are going to have good earnings growth in \uc2 GE Capital\uc2  over that time period.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: When is the \uc2 GE Capital\uc2  fix done?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: I really believe that a key catalyst both strategically and financially is when we start getting a dividend back from \uc2 GE Capital\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 WSJ: And is that next year?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: Unfortunately, I am not the one who decides it. Our expectation is 2012. That's what we told investors.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: On the industrial side, where specifically are you going to see meaningful growth?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: You've got aviation picking up steam. Health care saw double-digit growth last year, this year, and that should continue with a lot of growth globally. The transportation business is seeing good global growth and good infrastructure growth.\par \par \uc2 It comes to energy. Energy is a big one. The combination of better forecast for gas turbines plus an improving wind-turbine market outlook plus the acquisitions we've done. We like how that business is positioned for good growth into 2012.\par \par \uc2 So you rep all this up, and we're going to get I would say mid-single-digit industrial earnings growth this year. We should see accelerating earnings growth next year, even in the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  we see today.\par \par \uc2 And then if you look at it geographically, we're talking about all that counting on almost nothing from the U.S. In other words, we don't think we're going to get resurging energy growth at least in gas turbines in the U.S. maybe until '13.\par \par \uc2 More than 60% of our revenue is outside the United States, and probably 70% of our backlog is outside the United States. We think we're going to be powered by global markets for a long time.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Will GE's U.S. businesses shrink this year?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: I think the U.S. will be flattish this year. It's hard, because this is where \uc2 GE Capital\uc2  is the biggest.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Looking at your emerging markets, in Brazil you are seeding all your businesses there; in China you have missed your targeted $10 billion in revenue. Can you talk about these two markets as far as their growth prospects?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: We like having a diversified portfolio globally. We are not just China-dependent. We see good growth opportunities in Brazil and the Middle East and Russia and a lot of different places.\par \par \uc2 The middle class is growing in a place like Brazil, so as that happens health care grows, electricity grows. When I am in a country like Brazil, we have gas-turbine growth, wind-turbine growth, oil and gas growth, health-care growth, really diversified strong capability.\par \par \uc2 China always is going to be important. It is like 20% of our emerging-market portfolio right now. When we made the $10 billion goal, it was with an expectation that \uc2 GE Capital\uc2  was going to between $2 billion and $3 billion of our revenue. We had high aspirations, probably too high aspirations, for our \uc2 GE Capital\uc2  franchise. We have beat our goals in aviation and health care. The place where we have missed has been in energy, and that is because over the past couple of years there has been a strong focus in China on nuclear power and coal, both technologies that GE really doesn't really compete in in China. That has been the biggest head wind.\par \par \uc2 Looking forward in the future, I think aviation is going to continue to be great in China. Health care is on fire in China. Those are going to be strong. Energy, actually, I am actually quite optimistic about. I see more interest in gas turbines in China than I've seen in five years. And wind, we now have a better way to participate in China in wind. We ought to see a good 15% to 20% revenue growth in China over the next few years.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Is the strength of your business in Brazil because you decided to put a research and development center there?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: It's a lot of things coming together. We've been there a long time, but we've become more of an insider. We have great relationships with the big oil companies. We've got great relationships with the big banks. And then we have big capability. We have big locomotive capability. Our biggest aviation-service shop is in Brazil. We're building the research center there. So I think we're able to connect a lot of dots there. Something we try to do everywhere is use the breadth to the advantage. In global markets, that really pays.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Having built up wind and oil and gas, what's next on the horizon?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: We're going to stay in infrastructure. We always have a group of infrastructure adjacencies that are under way. What we would really like to do is take the things we've started and give them more scale. So if you look for instance at life sciences and look at avionics\u8212\'20\'14if you take avionics, we were a No. 3 or No. 4 competitor. I think we need to scale some of those key technologies before we take on something completely new. We might launch at $1 billion or $2 billion, but what we want are these core businesses to get above $5 billion in revenue over time. I think that will be the immediate focus.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: What are your regrets?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: I would say we let \uc2 GE Capital\uc2  get too big. We just let the balance sheet get too big. I don't think we were ever careless about it, but I think we didn't ask all of the right questions, and I regret that, and that's on me. There are other ones, but that one kind of dwarfs everything else.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: How involved do you get in acquisitions such as the purchase of \uc2 John Wood Group PLC\uc2 's well-support division and winning orders like the AirAsia engine order?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: I always believed you do these jobs retail and not wholesale. So I spend a lot of time traveling getting to know people, and that is advantageous when sometimes you need the ability to close a deal. I would say I was personally involved with Sir Ian [Wood], and we negotiated the deal on the phone in a way only two CEOs could do. I know Tony Fernandes from the time he started AirAsia. Tony was on my doorstep like a week after 9/11 trying to start his airline.\par \par \uc2 One of the ideas around GE\u8212\'20\'14that the CEO has tenure\u8212\'20\'14is really about relationships and being able to do things retail. I've done the job for 10 years. I think Hitachi has had five CEOs in that time. One of the advantages to tenure is you know a lot of people and can work things retail. And every now and then that is what is required.\par \par \uc2 I think it is personal presence. It is picking up the phone and calling out of sequence. I'll pick up the phone and call people when I don't need anything. Or go see them when I don't need anything. And if you do this over a long enough period of time, you build a certain amount of trust. Where you are not hunting together or golfing together, but you build up trust.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Your critics charge that you have overpaid for some acquisitions and been late in some of your divestitures. How do you respond?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: I defy any investor to say the plastics and insurance dispositions weren't a home run, a grand-slam home run for those investors. NBC, let's see. In other words, I say, it's early.\par \par \uc2 On the buy side, our industrial return on total capital is 18% this year. Our cost of capital is 9% to 10%. Our return on total capital as an industrial company is better than \uc2 Siemens\uc2 , Danaher, \uc2 Honeywell\uc2 . You name it, we're better. Wind was a great deal, Amersham is an OK deal, and the water deals stink. So you can't do a lot of deals and have them all be great. But on balance, our returns are superior to almost all the other industrial companies that we are compared with. That's my answer to the critics.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: The water deals stink, but you are holding onto them?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: Yeah, because again if you weren't in the business, you'd [want to] be in the business\u8212\'20\'14shortage of water, it's a good partner with many of our energy markets. When I'm talking to power companies, when I'm talking to biofuel companies, when I am talking to oil and gas companies, they all buy equipment in water technology, so I like the space. And therefore, over the long term, I am convinced we will make good returns for investors.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Critics charge you are more distant than your predecessor from the top officers and executives.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: I think that is bull\u8212\'20\'14. I think it is complete and utterly, totally not true. I've worked here for almost 30 years. For the last three years, I've spent weeks with the key leaders. I've known [\uc2 GE Energy\uc2  CEO] John Krenicki for 30 years. I've picked all of these people. I think there are some things that we can talk about like how the deals work, and that is debatable. This is one that is not debatable.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: What do you say to someone like [\uc2 Medtronic\uc2  CEO] \uc2 Omar Ishrak\uc2  who comes in and resigns?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: Every one is different. I always say you never dislike somebody more than the five minutes they are in your office resigning. I always take it personally. In the case of Omar, this is a great job. In that particular case, I can only wish him well. There's other times when I see people leave at the wrong time for the wrong job. I might give them different advice than what I gave Omar. I don't want people to leave the company. I still think the GE leadership brand speaks for itself.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Are you around for another 10 years?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: I feel good. I have passion for the company. I bring heat for all the things I do every day. I don't really think about it. I don't have a contract. I am as paranoid as the next CEO about everything. I don't feel like I have any kind of destiny other than working my ass off and trying my best. I still feel like doing that. I love the work; I love the people and I am committed to it.\par \par \uc2 I have lots of passion for it. I'm looking forward to an easier decade. I think there have been easier times to run a company other than the last decade. That's no excuse. That's true for everybody who has been running a company.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Are you still planning to sell appliances?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: I don't think about it really. In other words, we are putting a ton of money into lighting and appliances right now. I think we can run the business a lot better than we have over the past five years. That is my entire focus right now. We're investing to make the business better.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Your role as the chairman of President Obama's job council [Council on Jobs and Competitiveness] has generated a lot of criticism, as has the fact that GE paid little U.S. taxes last year. Is it hurting GE's reputation?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: We do very frequent surveys of GE, and the brand reputation is still very strong, bad press aside. I am going to give you an answer that is not very pleasing, and that is the reason why I am leading the jobs council is because I thought it was the right thing to do. I am not running for anything. I don't really have any political interest or aspirations. The U.S. government buys less than 3% of our revenue in 2011. It's not about political access. It's just that I thought this was a way to be helpful, and that's why I did it. In the U.S., it is controversial. Outside the U.S., people say, gosh, that's great. It's the times we live in.\par \par \uc2 As to the tax piece, we have been among a chorus of other people who said we believe in broad corporate tax reform. We've said that for years. We'd take the German system or the U.K. system or Japanese system\u8212\'20\'14or just about any other developed country that has a lower corporate tax rate and no loopholes, so let's go.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: You once said that jobs were the currency of the 21st century.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: There is high unemployment everywhere. There is high unemployment in the U.S., but there is high unemployment in China, there is high unemployment in India, there is high unemployment in Saudi Arabia. And I think that people do a better job of associating companies with job creation than they ever have in the past. When you run a company, you're not going to please everybody all the time on that. But you've got to be aware of it. It doesn't matter what you do on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  or funding for education. People want work. People want to see people being committed to their countries.\par \par \uc2 We are still a big exporter from the U.S., and I think that will continue for a long time. I am never going to apologize for globalizing GE\u8212\'20\'1490% of our aircraft engines leave the country; 100% of our gas turbines leave the country; 50% of our locomotives leave the country. That is where the customers are.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Are the days of double-digit growth gone for GE\u8212\'20\'14if for no other reason because you are so big?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Immelt: I think when you get big, it is harder. You have to be doing more things well to continue to drive the same growth. If I look at the combination of infrastructure and financial services of where GE is today, we should be able to grow through the cycles equal or greater than the S&P 500. I feel pretty good about our ability to do that where we are today. Now, it is hard to do that when you are selling 40% of the company, going through big dispositions and portfolio changes. But over the last decade, I think only Exxon and Shell have earned more money than we have. It's not like we thought we were taking years off. We just went from a 60 P/E to a 10 or 12 or 15.\par \par \uc2 Investors own the company. We need to repiver for them. If you look at a 30-year stock chart, we are OK. If you look at a 10-year stock chart, we've underperformed. But in the end, if I look at the company today looking forward, we have a great portfolio, we've invested in good products, we're in the right markets. I feel good.\par \par \uc2 We have done the things we said we were going to do with the company. I think investors are what they are. There is not one company in the world that wouldn't die for our infrastructure portfolio. Not one. And financial services, we have weathered the storm as well as anybody, and we are well positioned to come out the other side. Investors are going to have to triangulate what they think that set of financial-service earnings are worth. But the infrastructure earnings speak for themselves.\par \par \uc2 Write to Kate Linebaugh at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mailto:kate.linebaugh@wsj.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 kate.linebaugh@wsj.com }}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gnelc : \uc2 General Electric Company | gecapt : \uc2 General Electric Capital Corporation\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0