lpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Wealth creation\par \par \uc2 Amid fuzzy details, there will no longer be one approach, write Elizabeth Rigby and Andrew Bounds\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Ed Miliband will chart a fresh course for Labour's relations with the business community today, as he promises to recast a "neutral" stance in favour of one that rewards the good companies and penalises the bad.\par \par \uc2 However, beyond the rhetoric, there is little meat on the bones. The Labour leader's advisers are vague about how Labour intends to measure a "good company" or penalise the "asset strippers" that he attacks in his speech today.\par \par \uc2 He has yet to canvass the views of business or put together any specific policies.\par \par \uc2 If details are not yet forthcoming, the thrust is clear: no longer will there be a single approach to business. Instead, Mr Miliband wants to create a system in which rewards and incentives are linked to the long-term value businesses create and the wealth they build.\par \par \uc2 While the policy is fuzzy, the language he uses is likely to spark consternation among private equity companies and hedge funds, who may worry that the Labour leader appears to be reviving the Social Democratic tradition of attacking such industries.\par \par \uc2 Trade unions in the UK, Germany, Canada and elsewhere have long pointed to the damage caused by leveraged buy-outs.\par \par \uc2 And the "new bargain" with business that Mr Miliband is setting out is not really all that new. Vince Cable used his 2010 speech to the Liberal Democrat conference to announce an inquiry into corporate governance rules, with take-overs and pay both in the spotlight as the business secretary promised to "shine a harsh light into the murky world of corporate behaviour".\par \par \uc2 Mr Cable's department has been looking at "short-termism and shareholder disengagement", trying to find ways to re-engage shareholders with the companies they own.\par \par \uc2 But in practice, regulating "short-termism" in trading practices or takeover situations is extremely difficult and Mr Cable's department has yet to come up with specific policy recommendations.\par \par \uc2 Instead, Mr Cable is focusing his attention on more tangible goals, such as moderating executive pay - he pledged to stamp out reward for failure at last week's Lib Dem conference - and increasing diversity on FTSE boards.\par \par \uc2 Chuka Umunna, shadow business minister and an ally of Mr Miliband, on Monday tried to flesh out what a "good company" might look like, telling a fringe event that good companies were the ones that looked after their workers and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Labour is clear that businesses that secure government contracts will be required to offer young people apprenticeships, while the tax system could also be used to reward companies for investing in research and development and training.\par \par \uc2 "If you are a good company you have got nothing to worry about," Mr Umunna told an audience of business leaders at the British Chambers of Commerce fringe event. "We are recognising something that business people tell us. It is not all about the bottom line. Yes, they want to be prosperous but they also care a huge amount about their communities," he said.\par \par \uc2 But business leaders are sceptical about such meddling. Peter Marks, chief executive of the Co-operative, who shared the platform, said the market would drive such change anyway.\par \par \uc2 The UK's largest mutually owned retailer has embraced Fair Trade products and apprenticeships and its bank and asset management arm turns down investments on ethical grounds.\par \par \uc2 "We do not want government to start regulating \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Any company that does not take \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  seriously is doomed to fail in my view. The market is going to drive them and consumers are going to drive them."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c42 : \uc2 Labor/Personnel Issues | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpin : \uc2 FC&E Industry News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IPC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 CN\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\c