 and paste FT articles and redistribute by email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Tesco, Britain's largest retailer and one of the world's largest supermarket chains, has a fleet of vehicles commensurate with its size.\par \par \uc2 In the UK, it operates 1,600 tractor units and 2,800 home delivery vans. Tesco says its British secondary distribution alone covers the same mileage every year as 377 round trips to the moon. On a daily basis, the fleet's mileage would circle the earth 20 times, the company boasts.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 But Tesco - like most other big companies in all sectors - is aiming for superlatives of another kind, as it seeks to cut costs and to reduce the environmental footprint of its fleet.\par \par \uc2 The company says that its carbon reduction initiatives have saved 83m miles worth of trips. As part of its \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  goals, Tesco aims to be carbon-neutral by 2050, and to cut its carbon emissions on its deliveries 50 per cent by the 2012-13 financial year, compared with 2006-7.\par \par \uc2 Alex Laffey, Tesco's network development director, says the company's focus on stringent environmental goals is no gimmick - although he is also clear in stating that cutting CO2 also helps the bottom line. "Reducing carbon reduces cost," he says.\par \par \uc2 Like other big fleet operators committed to cutting CO2, Tesco has tested alternative vehicles. For its home-shopping fleet, it has done road trials on electric and gas-powered vehicles. In commercial vehicles, it has tested dual-fuel vehicles that switch between diesel and compressed natural gas (CNG).\par \par \uc2 However, in the case of gas-powered vehicles the company has struggled with the lack of supply infrastructure. It considered putting in gas stations at its distribution centres, but concluded that the cost of installation was too high.\par \par \uc2 For electric vehicles, it has grappled with range, infrastructure, and performance issues.\par \par \uc2 "The challenge we've got is that you're always trading off payload for the privilege of using these technologies," says Mr Laffey.\par \par \uc2 "We've got a lot of work to do to make these [vehicles] sustainable and cost-effective."\par \par \uc2 Tesco's progress in moving toward its CO2-reduction target, he says, comes down to reducing the amount of diesel it uses.\par \par \uc2 Tesco refers to its carbon commitment internally as the "F Plan", shorthand for its push for fuller pallets, fuller trucks, fewer miles, and greater fuel economy.\par \par \uc2 For example, the company has boosted its use of double-deck trailers, carrying 80 per cent more than a conventional single-deck trailer at just a 20 per cent higher cost. Tesco now runs more than 600 of them, the largest fleet in the UK, it says.\par \par \uc2 The company has shifted more of its goods to trains, running three a day, six days a week. It aims to increase the number to 10 by the end of the financial year.\par \par \uc2 Tesco is also investing heavily in technology that provides the exact weight and size of every product, so vehicles can be filled more accurately.\par \par \uc2 In a further attempt to cut fuel consumption, it is relocating depots to the optimum location for the stores in their region.\par \par \uc2 Overseas, where Tesco operates in 14 countries, its international businesses are also leveraging the group's scale and skills to cut costs.\par \par \uc2 In Thailand, for example, the chain is rolling out a transport management system that it expects will save 8,600 tonnes of CO2 in 2011-12.\par \par \uc2 The fleet, like many of its competitors, is also focusing on human factors by looking at driver behaviour.\par \par \uc2 The company uses Mercedes-Benz's FleetBoard system to score drivers on how well they are performing in terms of fuel consumption, and to highlight fuel-wasting practices such as revving the engine at lights.\par \par \uc2 Additional driver training has also increased efficiency by 8 per cent in miles per gallon terms, the company says.\par \par \uc2 "Our drivers are very professional and proud of what they do," Mr Laffey says.\par \par \uc2 But the company also expects its effect on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  to be influenced by other factors,- such as its rivals. It is also braced for an economic slowdown. "Conditions are tough and our customers are telling us they're finding it tough too," the company says.\par \par \uc2 So saving every drop of diesel is vital.\par \par \uc2 And on that count, Tesco looks to be motoring along: Mr Laffey says the company is "on track" to meet its carbon commitment by the end of the financial year.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15